{"title_page": "David Harding (financier)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          =\n| name                      = David Harding\n| image                     = File:David Harding 2016.png \n| image_size                =\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = David Winton Harding\n| birth_date                =   {{Birth year and age|1961|08}} \n| birth_place               = Oxford, England\n| nationality               = British\n| other_names               =\n| alma_mater                = [[University of Cambridge]]<br>[[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]] \n| occupation                = Investment Management\n| years_active              = 1982 to present\n| employer                  =\n| organization              =\n| known_for                 = Founder of [[Winton Group]]\n| home_town                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 = {{gain}}[[Pound Sterling|GB\u00a3]]1.1 [[1,000,000,000 (number)|billion]] (April 2016)<ref name=STRL>{{cite news|title=Sunday Times Rich List|work=The Sunday Times|issue=page 34|date=26 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/9789750/David-Harding-reports-hedge-fund-loss-in-2012.html|title=David Harding reports hedge fund loss in 2012|date=9 January 2013|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n| spouse                    =\n| partner                   =\n| children                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| signature_size            =\n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.winton.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 =\n| box_width                 =\n}}\n'''David Winton Harding''' (born August 1961) is a British billionaire businessperson, and the founder and CEO of [[Winton Group]].<ref name=Hallam /> He had previously co-founded [[Man Group|Man AHL]] (formerly Adam, Harding & Lueck).<ref name=\"Cohen 07\">{{cite news |title=Winton's Winning Formula |author=Barry Cohen |work=Absolute Return |date=November 2007}}</ref> His approach favours [[quantitative investing|quantitative investment]] strategies, using scientific research as the basis of trading decisions.\n\nHarding is also known for his [[philanthropy]], which includes a \u00a3100m donation to the [[University of Cambridge]], the largest ever donation by a British citizen to a university.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1be16ed6-289b-11e9-88a4-c32129756dd8|title=Cambridge university receives \u00a3100m in record UK donation|website=www.ft.com}}{{subscription requir</ref> Harding has also endowed the Winton Professor of the Public Understanding of Risk in the Statistical Laboratory at Cambridge's Faculty of Mathematics, and established the Harding Center for Risk Literacy at the [[Max Planck Institute for Human Development]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.charitycommission.gov.uk/charity-details/?regid=1120878&subid=0|title=Charity Details|website=beta.charitycommission.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nWith respect to scientific research, he has established a research programme into the physics of sustainability at Cambridge University's [[Cavendish Laboratory]]. Politically, Harding has served as the joint-treasurer of [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] and chairman of the BSIE finance committee.\n\n==Education and early career==\nDavid Winton Harding was born in August 1961.<ref name=CompaniesHouse>{{cite web|title=Winton Capital Management Limited|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/03311531/officers|website=Companies House|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> He was educated at the [[University of Cambridge]] where he attended [[St. Catharine's College, Cambridge|St. Catharine's College]].<ref name=CompaniesHouse/> At [[Cambridge]], Harding studied natural sciences and in 1982 he graduated from his BSc with [[British undergraduate degree classification#First-class honours|first class honours]].<ref name=\"Review 09\"/><ref name=\"FOW 06\"/> Later that year he began a traineeship at Wood Mackenzie, a stockbroker.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\">{{cite news |title=The Wizard of Winton |author=Leah McGrath Goodman |work=TraderDaily.com |date = April 2008|page=106}}</ref> After two years, he joined the futures brokerage firm, Johnson Matthey & Wallace, as a trader in [[commodity futures]].<ref name=\"Review 09\"/><ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mocatta Futures to buy JMB's brokerage unit. | work=American Metal Market | date=22 July 1986 | author=Roberta C. Yafie | url=http://business.highbeam.com/436402/article-1G1-4345875/mocatta-futures-buy-jmb-brokerage-unit | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728004613/http://business.highbeam.com/436402/article-1G1-4345875/mocatta-futures-buy-jmb-brokerage-unit | url-status=dead | archive-date=28 July 2014 | accessdate=14 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Investment management==\nIn 1985, Harding became a futures trader at Sabre Fund Management, one of the first [[commodity trading advisor]]s (CTAs) in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Willoughby 09\">{{cite news |title=Trend Tracker |author=Jack Willoughby |magazine=Barron's Hedge Funds |date=29 June 2009 }}</ref> He drew on his scientific background to design trading programs for futures markets.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> He remained with the firm for two years,<ref name=\"FOW 06\"/> until founding Adam, Harding & Lueck (AHL) in 1987 with Michael Adam and Martin Lueck.<ref name=\"FOW 06\">{{cite news |title=Profile: Winton wonderland |work=FOW Magazine |date=October 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/><ref name=\"Willoughby 09\"/>\n\nThe firm created AHL as a quantitatively focused CTA.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> In 1989, ED & F Man (which later became the [[Man Group]]) purchased a 51 percent stake in the firm.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> When Man bought the whole firm in 1994,<ref name=\"Hedgeworld 09\"/><ref name=\"Review 09\">{{cite news |title=A Head for Numbers |magazine=Hedge Fund Review |date=August 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"FOW 06\"/><ref name=\"Willoughby 09\"/> Harding became head of Man Quantitative Research.<ref name=\"FOW 06\"/><ref>{{cite news | title=Profile: Winton wonderland \u2013 David Harding's Winton Capital takes a stand against rising exchange fees | url=http://www.fow.com/Article/1386039/Issue/26557/Profile-Winton-wonderland.html | date=1 October 2006 | publisher=Futures & Options World (FOW) | accessdate=14 June 2013 }}</ref> In 1996, he left to set up his own firm. According to ''Barron's'', Harding had left Man after becoming frustrated by lack of focus on research and the bureaucracy of working in a large firm.<ref name=\"Hedgeworld 09\"/><ref name=\"Willoughby 09\"/>\n\n===Winton Group===\nHarding founded [[Winton Group|Winton]], an investment management firm, in 1997. It was named after his middle name and his father's first name.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"FOW 06\"/> According to ''Hedge Fund Review'' magazine, his aim was to demonstrate that a business can be successful based on [[Empiricism|empirical]] [[Scientific method|scientific]] research, rather than relying on marketing.<ref name=\"Review 09\"/> Harding recruited scientists to the firm to create a strong research environment<ref name=\"McIntosh 7 Oct\">{{cite news |title=GSAM Fund Buys Stake in Winton |author=Bill McIntosh |work=HedgeWorld Daily News |date=8 October 2007}}</ref> and to use quantitative, statistical research of market data to inform his trading decisions.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/>\n\nThe fund had been launched in 1997 with $1.6 million in assets; as of 2013, the fund had returned on average 15% net per year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Winton Futures Fund: Winton Capital Management |author=Margie Lindsay |url=http://m.risk.nqlnginx.incbase.net/hedge-funds-review/profile/2274157/winton-futures-fund-winton-capital-management |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140616174730/http://m.risk.nqlnginx.incbase.net/hedge-funds-review/profile/2274157/winton-futures-fund-winton-capital-management |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 June 2014 |work=[[Risk (magazine)|Risk]] |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2014 }}</ref> {{As of|2016|02}}, Winton had over $30 billion in [[assets under management]].<ref name=ValueWalk16>{{cite news |title=Managed Futures AUM: How Big is It Exactly? |url=http://www.valuewalk.com/2016/02/managed-futures-aum-2015/ |work=ValueWalk |date=24 February 2016 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHarding has been described by industry commentators as \"one of the pioneers of the hedge fund industry\".<ref name=\"Cohen 07\"/><ref name=\"Hedgeworld 09\">{{cite news |title=Harding's Hedge Fund Thrives on Surprise |work=Reuters Hedgeworld |date=16 October 2009}}</ref> He has been ranked among the top 50 hedge fund managers worldwide by [[Absolute Return + Alpha|''Alpha'' magazine]],<ref name=\"Griffith 08\">{{cite news |title=Finance at its very highest; Britain's biggest private companies |author=Katherine Griffiths |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph (London) |date=19 August 2008 |page=7}}</ref> which added him to their \"Hedge Fund Hall of Fame\",<ref>{{cite journal |year=2014 |title=Alpha Hedge Fund Hall of Fame:The Iconoclasts |journal=[[Absolute Return + Alpha|Alpha]] |volume=8 |publisher=Euromoney Institutional Investor }}</ref> and he was listed at 95 on the [[Sunday Times Rich List 2016|''Sunday Times'' Rich List 2016]].<ref name=RichList16>{{cite news |title=Rich List 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/rich-lists |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=24 April 2016 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he was reported to be London's highest paid earner at \u00a360m a year.<ref name=Fernandez10>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1315366/David-Harding-Citys-highest-earner-60m-year.html|title=Rambler with an interest in Bible studies is the City's highest earner on \u00a360m a year|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=19 March 2013|location=London|first=Colin|last=Fernandez|date=26 September 2010}}</ref> In September 2012, Harding was named at the top of a list of Britain's biggest taxpayers.<ref name=Newlands14/> Within 6 days, Harding revealed that \"he was paying \u00a334 million in tax on his \u00a387m income.\"<ref name=Hellen>{{cite news |title=Rich man pays his taxes \u2013 shock |author=Nicholas Hellen |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/National/article1137210.ece |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hedge fund founder David Harding reveals \u00a334m tax bill |author=Matthew Sparkes |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/9576928/Hedge-fund-founder-David-Harding-reveals-34m-tax-bill.html#mm_hash |work=The Telegraph |date=30 September 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 he became the firm's majority owner.<ref name=Agnew>{{cite news |title=David Harding realises dream at Winton |author=Harriet Agnew |url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2012-01-24/david-harding-winton-overtakes-ahl |work=E-Financial News |date=24 January 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> Harding had previously served as Winton's president and executive chairman.<ref name=Hallam>{{cite news |title=Goldman Partner to Help Raise Funds for Crick Institute |author=Kristen Hallam |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-22/goldman-partner-to-help-raise-funds-for-crick-institute.html |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=22 April 2013 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=Wright>{{cite news |title=Winton Capital Plans Expansion Drive With Up To 100 New Hires By Year-End |author=Ben Wright |url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304585004579415352193013552 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> In 2015 he became CEO.<ref name=\"Agnew\"/>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHarding has made major donations to educational and research institutions through his Winton Charitable Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charitiesdirect.com/charities/the-winton-charitable-foundation-1110131.html |title=The Winton Charitable Foundation |work=charitiesdirect.com |publisher=Charities Direct |accessdate=30 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405061600/http://www.charitiesdirect.com/charities/the-winton-charitable-foundation-1110131.html |archive-date=5 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The foundation funded a professorship at the Statistical Laboratory of the University of Cambridge, the [[Winton Professorship of the Public Understanding of Risk]], aimed at increasing understanding of the mathematics of risk for individuals and organisations.<ref name=\"Review 09\"/><ref name=\"McIntosh 7 Oct\"/><ref name=\"Risk 07\">{{cite web |url=http://news.admin.cam.ac.uk/news/2007/01/12/cambridgeappointsprofessorofrisk-2/ |title=Cambridge appoints Professor of Risk |date=12 January 2007 |work=news.admin.cam.ac.uk |publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> Harding is also the patron of the Harding Center for Risk Literacy at the [[Max Planck Institute for Human Development]] in [[Berlin]],<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> which opened in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpib-berlin.mpg.de/en/media/2009/04/new-harding-center-for-risk-literacy |title=New Harding Center for Risk Literacy |date=21 April 2009 |work=mpib-berlin.mpg.de |publisher=Max Planck Institute for Human Development |accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHarding's foundation, the David and Claudia Harding Foundation, has pledged \u00a320 million to the [[University of Cambridge]]'s [[Cavendish Laboratory]] to establish The Winton Programme for the Physics of Sustainability, an advanced research programme to apply theoretical physics to issues of the sustainability of natural resources.<ref name=\"Rich List 2014\">{{cite web |url=http://features.thesundaytimes.co.uk/richlist/2014/live/richlist/view/group6/1/rank/-/harding#list |title=Rich List 2014 |date=18 May 2014|work=The Sunday Times|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sustainability 11\">{{cite web |url=http://news.admin.cam.ac.uk/news/2011/03/24/physicsofsustainabilityprogrammelaunchedatcavendish/ |title=Physics of sustainability programme launched at Cavendish |date=24 March 2011 |work=news.admin.cam.ac.uk |publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Cavendish 10\">{{cite web |url=http://news.admin.cam.ac.uk/news/2010/11/15/20milliondonationtorevolutionisephysicsresearch/ |title=\u00a320 million donation to revolutionise physics research |date=15 November 2010 |work=news.admin.cam.ac.uk |publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> The donation to the [[Cavendish Laboratory|Cavendish]] is the largest since the famous laboratory was established in 1874.<ref name=\"Cavendish 10\"/> Harding is one of the administrators of the Winton Fund for the Physics of Sustainability, which manages the programme's funding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.winton.phy.cam.ac.uk/WintonBrochure |title=Winton Programme for the Physics of Sustainability Inaugural Celebration |date=24 March 2011 |work=winton.phy.cam.ac.uk |publisher=Winton Programme for the Physics of Sustainability |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Winton began a five-year sponsorship of the [[Royal Society Prizes for Science Books]] which was rechristened the Royal Society Winton Prize for Science Books.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Society Winton Prize for Science Books Shortlist Announced|url=http://royalsociety.org/news/Royal-Society-Winton-Prize-for-Science-Books-Shortlist-Announced/|work=royalsociety.org}}</ref> Harding's foundation has also committed \u00a35m to the [[Francis Crick Institute]] in London for [[cancer research]].<ref name=\"Rich List 2014\"/> In 2014, it provided a \u00a35 million donation to the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]] in London, the largest single donation in the museum's history, to build a gallery of mathematics.<ref name=Bellos14>{{cite news |title=Science Museum unveils \u00a35m plan for 'world's foremost' mathematics gallery |author=Alex Bellos |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/sep/10/science-museum-design-mathematics-gallery-maths |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=Jury14>{{cite news |title=Hedge fund boss gives \u00a35\u2009million to build new museum maths gallery |author=Louise Jury |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/hedge-fund-boss-gives-5million-to-build-new-museum-maths-gallery-9723563.html |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=Bellos14/><ref name=Dex14>{{cite news |title=\u00a35m Zaha Hadid-designed maths gallery for Science Museum |author=Robert Dex |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/architecture/5m-zaha-hadiddesigned-maths-gallery-for-science-museum-9724818.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Harding donated \u00a3100m to [[Cambridge University]], the largest donation by a British citizen to any university. The funds will go towards supporting the Harding Scholars, a distinguished postgraduate scholarship system for more than 100 PhD students, similar to the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] and the [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]].<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-47127690|title=David Harding's \u00a3100m gift to Cambridge University&#124;date=5 February 2019}}</ref> Additional funding will be used to attract students from under-represented groups, allowing Cambridge to recruit the best and brightest students regardless of their social situation. Harding's \u00a3100m benefaction was a landmark donation for UK fundraising efforts and closely followed other major donations by leading US entrepreneurs including [[Michael Bloomberg]], [[Stephen Schwarzman]], and [[Jaffray Woodriff]].<ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n\n==Other roles==\nIn November 2015, he was announced as joint-treasurer of [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] and chairman of the finance committee.<ref name=Hellier15>{{cite news |title=Leading hedge fund manager backs campaign to stay in EU |author=David Hellier |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/12/leading-hedge-fund-manager-david-harding-campaign-stay-eu |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 November 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, it was announced that Harding had donated \u00a33.5 million to the campaign.<ref name=Fortson16>{{cite news |title=EU vote: money men unveiled |author=Danny Fortson |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/eu-vote-money-men-unveiled-33pn9dlr9 |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=1 May 2016 |accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=Winning16>{{cite news |title=Pro-Brexit Groups Gain Funding Edge in Run-Up to EU Referendum |author1=Nicholas Winning |author2=Lawrence Fletcher |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pro-brexit-groups-gain-funding-edge-in-run-up-to-eu-referendum-1462973775 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nHarding has five children<ref>{{cite news |title=An audience with David Harding: A second referendum? 'F*ck no' |author=Chris Newlands |newspaper=Financial News |date=24 September 2018 |accessdate=15 October 2018| url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/an-audience-with-david-harding-a-second-referendum-fck-no-20180924}}</ref> and is married to Claudia Harding.<ref name=Williamson14>{{cite news |title=Harding helps London museum open a gallery dedicated to math |author=Christine Williamson |url=http://www.pionline.com/article/20140915/PRINT/309159989/harding-helps-london-museum-open-a-gallery-dedicated-to-math |work=Pensions & Investments |date=15 September 2014 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=Newlands14>{{cite news |title=Winton: 'People are frightened of us' |author=Chris Newlands|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/ca73ff3a-e7e7-11e3-b923-00144feabdc0.html|work=[[Financial Times]] |date=1 June 2014 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harding, David}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English billionaires]]\n[[Category:English stockbrokers]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English investors]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:English stock traders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          =\n| name                      = David Harding\n| image                     = File:David Harding 2016.png \n| image_size                =\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = David Winton Harding\n| birth_date                =   {{Birth year and age|1961|08}} \n| birth_place               = Oxford, England\n| nationality               = British\n| other_names               =\n| alma_mater                = [[University of Cambridge]]<br>[[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]] \n| occupation                = Investment Management\n| years_active              = 1982 to present\n| employer                  =\n| organization              =\n| known_for                 = Founder of [[Winton Group]]\n| home_town                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 = {{gain}}[[Pound Sterling|GB\u00a3]]1.1 [[1,000,000,000 (number)|billion]] (April 2016)<ref name=STRL>{{cite news|title=Sunday Times Rich List|work=The Sunday Times|issue=page 34|date=26 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/9789750/David-Harding-reports-hedge-fund-loss-in-2012.html|title=David Harding reports hedge fund loss in 2012|date=9 January 2013|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n| spouse                    =\n| partner                   =\n| children                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| signature_size            =\n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.winton.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 =\n| box_width                 =\n}}\n'''David Winton Harding''' (born August 1961) is a British billionaire businessperson, and the founder and CEO of [[Winton Group]].<ref name=Hallam /> He had previously co-founded [[Man Group|Man AHL]] (formerly Adam, Harding & Lueck).<ref name=\"Cohen 07\">{{cite news |title=Winton's Winning Formula |author=Barry Cohen |work=Absolute Return |date=November 2007}}</ref> His approach favours [[quantitative investing|quantitative investment]] strategies, using scientific research as the basis of trading decisions.\n\nHarding is also known for his [[philanthropy]], which includes a \u00a3100m donation to the [[University of Cambridge]], the largest ever donation by a British citizen to a university.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1be16ed6-289b-11e9-88a4-c32129756dd8|title=Cambridge university receives \u00a3100m in record UK donation|website=www.ft.com}}{{subscription requir</ref> Harding has also endowed the Winton Professor of the Public Understanding of Risk in the Statistical Laboratory at Cambridge's Faculty of Mathematics, and established the Harding Center for Risk Literacy at the [[Max Planck Institute for Human Development]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.charitycommission.gov.uk/charity-details/?regid=1120878&subid=0|title=Charity Details|website=beta.charitycommission.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nWith respect to scientific research, he has established a research programme into the physics of sustainability at Cambridge University's [[Cavendish Laboratory]]. Politically, Harding has served as the joint-treasurer of [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] and chairman of the BSIE finance committee.\n\n==Education and early career==\nDavid Winton Harding was born in August 1961.<ref name=CompaniesHouse>{{cite web|title=Winton Capital Management Limited|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/03311531/officers|website=Companies House|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> He was educated at the [[University of Cambridge]] where he attended [[St. Catharine's College, Cambridge|St. Catharine's College]].<ref name=CompaniesHouse/> At [[Cambridge]], Harding studied natural sciences and in 1982 he graduated from his BSc with [[British undergraduate degree classification#First-class honours|first class honours]].<ref name=\"Review 09\"/><ref name=\"FOW 06\"/> Later that year he began a traineeship at Wood Mackenzie, a stockbroker.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\">{{cite news |title=The Wizard of Winton |author=Leah McGrath Goodman |work=TraderDaily.com |date = April 2008|page=106}}</ref> After two years, he joined the futures brokerage firm, Johnson Matthey & Wallace, as a trader in [[commodity futures]].<ref name=\"Review 09\"/><ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mocatta Futures to buy JMB's brokerage unit. | work=American Metal Market | date=22 July 1986 | author=Roberta C. Yafie | url=http://business.highbeam.com/436402/article-1G1-4345875/mocatta-futures-buy-jmb-brokerage-unit | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728004613/http://business.highbeam.com/436402/article-1G1-4345875/mocatta-futures-buy-jmb-brokerage-unit | url-status=dead | archive-date=28 July 2014 | accessdate=14 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Investment management==\nIn 1985, Harding became a futures trader at Sabre Fund Management, one of the first [[commodity trading advisor]]s (CTAs) in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Willoughby 09\">{{cite news |title=Trend Tracker |author=Jack Willoughby |magazine=Barron's Hedge Funds |date=29 June 2009 }}</ref> He drew on his scientific background to design trading programs for futures markets.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> He remained with the firm for two years,<ref name=\"FOW 06\"/> until founding Adam, Harding & Lueck (AHL) in 1987 with Michael Adam and Martin Lueck.<ref name=\"FOW 06\">{{cite news |title=Profile: Winton wonderland |work=FOW Magazine |date=October 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/><ref name=\"Willoughby 09\"/>\n\nThe firm created AHL as a quantitatively focused CTA.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> In 1989, ED & F Man (which later became the [[Man Group]]) purchased a 51 percent stake in the firm.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> When Man bought the whole firm in 1994,<ref name=\"Hedgeworld 09\"/><ref name=\"Review 09\">{{cite news |title=A Head for Numbers |magazine=Hedge Fund Review |date=August 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"FOW 06\"/><ref name=\"Willoughby 09\"/> Harding became head of Man Quantitative Research.<ref name=\"FOW 06\"/><ref>{{cite news | title=Profile: Winton wonderland \u2013 David Harding's Winton Capital takes a stand against rising exchange fees | url=http://www.fow.com/Article/1386039/Issue/26557/Profile-Winton-wonderland.html | date=1 October 2006 | publisher=Futures & Options World (FOW) | accessdate=14 June 2013 }}</ref> In 1996, he left to set up his own firm. According to ''Barron's'', Harding had left Man after becoming frustrated by lack of focus on research and the bureaucracy of working in a large firm.<ref name=\"Hedgeworld 09\"/><ref name=\"Willoughby 09\"/>\n\n===Winton Group===\nHarding founded [[Winton Group|Winton]], an investment management firm, in 1997. It was named after his middle name and his father's first name.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"FOW 06\"/> According to ''Hedge Fund Review'' magazine, his aim was to demonstrate that a business can be successful based on [[Empiricism|empirical]] [[Scientific method|scientific]] research, rather than relying on marketing.<ref name=\"Review 09\"/> Harding recruited scientists to the firm to create a strong research environment<ref name=\"McIntosh 7 Oct\">{{cite news |title=GSAM Fund Buys Stake in Winton |author=Bill McIntosh |work=HedgeWorld Daily News |date=8 October 2007}}</ref> and to use quantitative, statistical research of market data to inform his trading decisions.<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/>\n\nThe fund had been launched in 1997 with $1.6 million in assets; as of 2013, the fund had returned on average 15% net per year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Winton Futures Fund: Winton Capital Management |author=Margie Lindsay |url=http://m.risk.nqlnginx.incbase.net/hedge-funds-review/profile/2274157/winton-futures-fund-winton-capital-management |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140616174730/http://m.risk.nqlnginx.incbase.net/hedge-funds-review/profile/2274157/winton-futures-fund-winton-capital-management |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 June 2014 |work=[[Risk (magazine)|Risk]] |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2014 }}</ref> {{As of|2016|02}}, Winton had over $30 billion in [[assets under management]].<ref name=ValueWalk16>{{cite news |title=Managed Futures AUM: How Big is It Exactly? |url=http://www.valuewalk.com/2016/02/managed-futures-aum-2015/ |work=ValueWalk |date=24 February 2016 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHarding has been described by industry commentators as \"one of the pioneers of the hedge fund industry\".<ref name=\"Cohen 07\"/><ref name=\"Hedgeworld 09\">{{cite news |title=Harding's Hedge Fund Thrives on Surprise |work=Reuters Hedgeworld |date=16 October 2009}}</ref> He has been ranked among the top 50 hedge fund managers worldwide by [[Absolute Return + Alpha|''Alpha'' magazine]],<ref name=\"Griffith 08\">{{cite news |title=Finance at its very highest; Britain's biggest private companies |author=Katherine Griffiths |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph (London) |date=19 August 2008 |page=7}}</ref> which added him to their \"Hedge Fund Hall of Fame\",<ref>{{cite journal |year=2014 |title=Alpha Hedge Fund Hall of Fame:The Iconoclasts |journal=[[Absolute Return + Alpha|Alpha]] |volume=8 |publisher=Euromoney Institutional Investor }}</ref> and he was listed at 95 on the [[Sunday Times Rich List 2016|''Sunday Times'' Rich List 2016]].<ref name=RichList16>{{cite news |title=Rich List 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/rich-lists |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=24 April 2016 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he was reported to be London's highest paid earner at \u00a360m a year.<ref name=Fernandez10>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1315366/David-Harding-Citys-highest-earner-60m-year.html|title=Rambler with an interest in Bible studies is the City's highest earner on \u00a360m a year|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=19 March 2013|location=London|first=Colin|last=Fernandez|date=26 September 2010}}</ref> In September 2012, Harding was named at the top of a list of Britain's biggest taxpayers.<ref name=Newlands14/> Within 6 days, Harding revealed that \"he was paying \u00a334 million in tax on his \u00a387m income.\"<ref name=Hellen>{{cite news |title=Rich man pays his taxes \u2013 shock |author=Nicholas Hellen |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/National/article1137210.ece |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hedge fund founder David Harding reveals \u00a334m tax bill |author=Matthew Sparkes |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/9576928/Hedge-fund-founder-David-Harding-reveals-34m-tax-bill.html#mm_hash |work=The Telegraph |date=30 September 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 he became the firm's majority owner.<ref name=Agnew>{{cite news |title=David Harding realises dream at Winton |author=Harriet Agnew |url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2012-01-24/david-harding-winton-overtakes-ahl |work=E-Financial News |date=24 January 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> Harding had previously served as Winton's president and executive chairman.<ref name=Hallam>{{cite news |title=Goldman Partner to Help Raise Funds for Crick Institute |author=Kristen Hallam |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-22/goldman-partner-to-help-raise-funds-for-crick-institute.html |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=22 April 2013 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=Wright>{{cite news |title=Winton Capital Plans Expansion Drive With Up To 100 New Hires By Year-End |author=Ben Wright |url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304585004579415352193013552 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> In 2015 he became CEO.<ref name=\"Agnew\"/>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHarding has made major donations to educational and research institutions through his Winton Charitable Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charitiesdirect.com/charities/the-winton-charitable-foundation-1110131.html |title=The Winton Charitable Foundation |work=charitiesdirect.com |publisher=Charities Direct |accessdate=30 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405061600/http://www.charitiesdirect.com/charities/the-winton-charitable-foundation-1110131.html |archive-date=5 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The foundation funded a professorship at the Statistical Laboratory of the University of Cambridge, the [[Winton Professorship of the Public Understanding of Risk]], aimed at increasing understanding of the mathematics of risk for individuals and organisations.<ref name=\"Review 09\"/><ref name=\"McIntosh 7 Oct\"/><ref name=\"Risk 07\">{{cite web |url=http://news.admin.cam.ac.uk/news/2007/01/12/cambridgeappointsprofessorofrisk-2/ |title=Cambridge appoints Professor of Risk |date=12 January 2007 |work=news.admin.cam.ac.uk |publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> Harding is also the patron of the Harding Center for Risk Literacy at the [[Max Planck Institute for Human Development]] in [[Berlin]],<ref name=\"Goodman 08\"/> which opened in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpib-berlin.mpg.de/en/media/2009/04/new-harding-center-for-risk-literacy |title=New Harding Center for Risk Literacy |date=21 April 2009 |work=mpib-berlin.mpg.de |publisher=Max Planck Institute for Human Development |accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHarding's foundation, the David and Claudia Harding Foundation, has pledged \u00a320 million to the [[University of Cambridge]]'s [[Cavendish Laboratory]] to establish The Winton Programme for the Physics of Sustainability, an advanced research programme to apply theoretical physics to issues of the sustainability of natural resources.<ref name=\"Rich List 2014\">{{cite web |url=http://features.thesundaytimes.co.uk/richlist/2014/live/richlist/view/group6/1/rank/-/harding#list |title=Rich List 2014 |date=18 May 2014|work=The Sunday Times|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sustainability 11\">{{cite web |url=http://news.admin.cam.ac.uk/news/2011/03/24/physicsofsustainabilityprogrammelaunchedatcavendish/ |title=Physics of sustainability programme launched at Cavendish |date=24 March 2011 |work=news.admin.cam.ac.uk |publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Cavendish 10\">{{cite web |url=http://news.admin.cam.ac.uk/news/2010/11/15/20milliondonationtorevolutionisephysicsresearch/ |title=\u00a320 million donation to revolutionise physics research |date=15 November 2010 |work=news.admin.cam.ac.uk |publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> The donation to the [[Cavendish Laboratory|Cavendish]] is the largest since the famous laboratory was established in 1874.<ref name=\"Cavendish 10\"/> Harding is one of the administrators of the Winton Fund for the Physics of Sustainability, which manages the programme's funding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.winton.phy.cam.ac.uk/WintonBrochure |title=Winton Programme for the Physics of Sustainability Inaugural Celebration |date=24 March 2011 |work=winton.phy.cam.ac.uk |publisher=Winton Programme for the Physics of Sustainability |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Winton began a five-year sponsorship of the [[Royal Society Prizes for Science Books]] which was rechristened the Royal Society Winton Prize for Science Books.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Society Winton Prize for Science Books Shortlist Announced|url=http://royalsociety.org/news/Royal-Society-Winton-Prize-for-Science-Books-Shortlist-Announced/|work=royalsociety.org}}</ref> Harding's foundation has also committed \u00a35m to the [[Francis Crick Institute]] in London for [[cancer research]].<ref name=\"Rich List 2014\"/> In 2014, it provided a \u00a35 million donation to the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]] in London, the largest single donation in the museum's history, to build a gallery of mathematics.<ref name=Bellos14>{{cite news |title=Science Museum unveils \u00a35m plan for 'world's foremost' mathematics gallery |author=Alex Bellos |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/sep/10/science-museum-design-mathematics-gallery-maths |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=Jury14>{{cite news |title=Hedge fund boss gives \u00a35\u2009million to build new museum maths gallery |author=Louise Jury |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/hedge-fund-boss-gives-5million-to-build-new-museum-maths-gallery-9723563.html |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=Bellos14/><ref name=Dex14>{{cite news |title=\u00a35m Zaha Hadid-designed maths gallery for Science Museum |author=Robert Dex |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/architecture/5m-zaha-hadiddesigned-maths-gallery-for-science-museum-9724818.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Harding donated \u00a3100m to [[Cambridge University]], the largest donation by a British citizen to any university. The funds will go towards supporting the Harding Scholars, a distinguished postgraduate scholarship system for more than 100 PhD students, similar to the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] and the [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]].<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-47127690|title=David Harding's \u00a3100m gift to Cambridge University&#124;date=5 February 2019}}</ref> Additional funding will be used to attract students from under-represented groups, allowing Cambridge to recruit the best and brightest students regardless of their social situation. Harding's \u00a3100m benefaction was a landmark donation for UK fundraising efforts and closely followed other major donations by leading US entrepreneurs including [[Michael Bloomberg]], [[Stephen Schwarzman]], and [[Jaffray Woodriff]].<ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n\n==Other roles==\nIn November 2015, he was announced as joint-treasurer of [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] and chairman of the finance committee.<ref name=Hellier15>{{cite news |title=Leading hedge fund manager backs campaign to stay in EU |author=David Hellier |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/12/leading-hedge-fund-manager-david-harding-campaign-stay-eu |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 November 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, it was announced that Harding had donated \u00a33.5 million to the campaign.<ref name=Fortson16>{{cite news |title=EU vote: money men unveiled |author=Danny Fortson |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/eu-vote-money-men-unveiled-33pn9dlr9 |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=1 May 2016 |accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=Winning16>{{cite news |title=Pro-Brexit Groups Gain Funding Edge in Run-Up to EU Referendum |author1=Nicholas Winning |author2=Lawrence Fletcher |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pro-brexit-groups-gain-funding-edge-in-run-up-to-eu-referendum-1462973775 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nHarding has five children<ref>{{cite news |title=An audience with David Harding: A second referendum? 'F*ck no' |author=Chris Newlands |newspaper=Financial News |date=24 September 2018 |accessdate=15 October 2018| url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/an-audience-with-david-harding-a-second-referendum-fck-no-20180924}}</ref> and is married to Claudia Harding.<ref name=Williamson14>{{cite news |title=Harding helps London museum open a gallery dedicated to math |author=Christine Williamson |url=http://www.pionline.com/article/20140915/PRINT/309159989/harding-helps-london-museum-open-a-gallery-dedicated-to-math |work=Pensions & Investments |date=15 September 2014 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=Newlands14>{{cite news |title=Winton: 'People are frightened of us' |author=Chris Newlands|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/ca73ff3a-e7e7-11e3-b923-00144feabdc0.html|work=[[Financial Times]] |date=1 June 2014 |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harding, David}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English billionaires]]\n[[Category:English stockbrokers]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English investors]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:English stock traders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Harding_(financier)"}
{"title_page": "Robert Rowland", "text_new": "{{short description|Brexit Party politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Robert Rowland\n| honorific-suffix =\n| party = [[Brexit Party|Brexit]]\n| image = File:Robert ID London meeting Febuary 2020.jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[South East England (European Parliament constituency)|South East England]]\n| status = \n| term_start = [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2 July 2019]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/elections-press-kit/0/key-dates-ahead |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=28 May 2019 |date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48365702|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=28 May 2019 |date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[Ray Finch]]\n| successor   = ''Constituency abolished''\n| term_end = 31 January 2020\n| parliament = European\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|02|28|df=yes}}<ref name=europarl-bio>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/197733/ROBERT_ROWLAND/home |title=Robert ROWLAND |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Bowdon, Greater Manchester]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Lisa Marie\n| relations = \n| children = 4\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Newcastle University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Robert Andrew Rowland''' is a British politician who has served as a [[Brexit Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for [[South East England (European Parliament constituency)|South East England]] from 2019 until the [[Brexit|United Kingdom's exit from the EU]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=The UK's European elections 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/crjeqkdevwvt/the-uks-european-elections-2019 |website=BBC News |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref> He was a member of the [[European Parliament Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs|Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs]]  and is a substitute on the [[European Parliament Committee on Industry, Research and Energy|Committee for Industry, Research and Energy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/197733/ROBERT_ROWLAND/history/9|title=9th parliamentary term {{!}} Robert ROWLAND {{!}} MEPs {{!}} European Parliament|website=www.europarl.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nRowland graduated from the University of Newcastle in 1988 with a BA (Hons)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://google.brand.edgar-online.com/efxapi/EFX_dll/EDGARpro.dll?FetchFilingHtmlSection1?SectionID=4178759-460851-467122&SessionID=j5B7eFiYveEvTG7 |website=Edgar Online |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> and began his career in the investment industry. He started at [[Lazard Fr\u00e8res|Lazard Asset Management]], and then became a fund manager with [[Odey Asset Management]] before  becoming a director at Soros Fund Management <ref>{{cite web |title= Mr Robert Andrew Rowland |url=https://register.fca.org.uk/ShPo_individualdetailsPage?id=003b000000LUwtiAAD |website=Financial Conduct Authority |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> He then moved back to  Lazard Asset Management in New York, after which he became a partner at Cheyne Capital Management (UK). Rowland is a director of the charity 'Tickets for Troops'. The charity distributes free tickets to members of the armed forces for a variety of sporting, musical and cultural events.<ref name=ticketsfortroops-directors>{{cite web |url=https://www.ticketsfortroops.org.uk/about-us/the-directors.aspx |title=The Directors |publisher=Tickets for Troops |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nRowland's first introduction to politics was while he was studying at the University of Newcastle. He stood for Deputy President of the Student's Union in 1987,<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle University Courier |url=http://courierarchive.ncl.ac.uk/sites/default/files/1987-01-29.pdf |website=Newcastle University Library Courier Archive |accessdate=26 December 2019 |page=3 |date=29 January 1987}}</ref> and on failing to win that position, the 5 March 1987 issue of the student newspaper, the Courier, reports that he stood unopposed for election for the Convener of the Disciplinary Committee, but lost by 335 votes to 395 against \"Re-open Nominations (R.O.N).\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle University Courier |url=http://courierarchive.ncl.ac.uk/sites/default/files/1987-03-05.pdf |website=Newcastle University Library Courier Archive |accessdate=26 December 2019 |page=2 |date=5 March 1987}}</ref> \n\nIn the 10 March 1988 edition of the Courier, he wrote a letter directed at what he dubbed \"the fascist left,\" and defending freedom of speech, and opposing the practice of providing \"no platform\" to speakers whose views were considered objectionable by some.<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle University Courier |url=http://courierarchive.ncl.ac.uk/sites/default/files/1988-03-10.pdf |website=Newcastle University Library Courier Archive |accessdate=26 December 2019 |page=4 |date=10 March 1988}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019 Rowland chose to return to politics, and at a european level, by standing as a candidate for the [[Brexit Party]]. Rowland gave his first major speech as a candidate at the Lakeside Hotel in Frimley, Surrey in May of that year, where he described opposition to Brexit as a potential \"coup against democracy\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/may/25/farage-brexit-party-remain|title=The energy behind Farage and his Brexit party leaves his rivals in the shadows|first=John|last=Harris|date=25 May 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nRowland was elected third on the Brexit Party list for the South East of England in the European Parliament elections in May 2019. He sat on the ECON (Economic and Monetary Affairs) committee in the European Parliament. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/unitedkingdom/en/european-elections/uk_meps/south_east_region.html|title=South East Region - 10 MEPs|website=www.europarl.europa.eu}}</ref> \n\nHe is a [[climate change sceptic]], saying in a debate on 23 October 2019:\n\n{{quote|There is, frankly, more credibility with the theories such as sunspots, the Milankovitch cycle and orbital variations than there is with anthropogenic warming<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web |title=Debates: Wednesday, 23 October 2019 - Strasbourg |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/CRE-9-2019-10-23-INT-3-270-0000_EN.html |website=European Parliament |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the same speech he said \"decarbonisation is deindustrialisation. It amounts to unilateral disarmament.\"<ref name=\"climate\" /> He argued that decarbonisation policies replace tax revenues generated from fossil fuels with subsidies to the detriment of the funding public services.\n\nWriting for the Daily Telegraph in September 2019, Rowland warned that the UK was giving up a claim to accumulated profits from the European Investment Bank in the proposed European Union withdrawal agreement. In the same article he also argued that large eurozone liabilities and the highly leveraged way that the Bank lends puts it at risk of a banking crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rowland |first1=Robert |title=Bunging the EU billions of pounds for free shows the toxic ineptitude at the heart of May's Brexit deal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/30/bunging-eu-billions-pounds-free-shows-toxic-ineptitude-heart/ |accessdate=20 December 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\nOn 9 July 2019, Rowland's Twitter activities received national attention when he tweeted at [[David Lammy]], MP: \"Lammy, you\u2019re first port of call should be the Chicago School of Economics. Complete 3 years and then you might understand 10% of what we all understand. Ignorance and race baiting is your signature tune.\" Twitter users were quick to point out that he had made a grammar error; that the Chicago School of Economics is not an actual university, but a school of thought; and that American degrees would in any case require 4 years, not 3. David Lammy also pointed out that he had, in fact, attended Harvard University.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit Party MEP tried to come for David Lammy\u2019s education and he was the one who got schooled |url=https://www.indy100.com/article/brexit-party-mep-david-lammy-robert-rowland-twitter-university-chicago-8998641 |accessdate=26 November 2019 |work=The Independent |date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, on 10 July 2019, Rowland tweeted  \"We are behind all our fisherman and the restoration of sovereignty over our waters. 200 miles of exclusion zone with any foreign fishing vessel given the same treatment as the [[ARA General Belgrano|Belgrano]]! Well done June. We are 110% behind you and will ensure you give \u2018em hell on committee.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Rowland Brexit SE Twitter|URL=https://twitter.com/RowlandBrexitSE|website=Twitter|accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>  His threat to sink foreign civilian fishing vessels was widely shared and criticised on social media.<ref name=guardian-20190712>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/12/brexit-party-mep-criticised-over-belgrano-twitter-comments |title=Brexit party MEP called for EU fishing vessels to be 'sunk like Belgrano' |last=Rankin |first=Jennifer |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 July 2019 |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2019, he again received media attention when an exchange with Green Party MEP [[Molly Scott Cato]] in the European Parliament was broadcast. Rowland asked what experience Scott Cato had to allow her to comment on the economic aspects of Brexit, as he said she had no background in economics, nor even a degree. In reality, as highlighted by Scott Cato, she is a Professor of Economics at the  University of Roehampton.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jankowicz |first1=Mia |title=Brexit Party MEP makes himself laughing stock in EU parliament challenge |url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/robert-rowland-eu-parliament-molly-scott-cato-1-6395124 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |work=The New European |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRowland is married with three sons and one daughter.<ref name=ticketsfortroops-directors/>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{Brexit Party}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rowland, Robert}}\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-MEP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brexit Party politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Robert Rowland\n| honorific-suffix =\n| party = [[Brexit Party|Brexit]]\n| image = File:Robert ID London meeting Febuary 2020.jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[South East England (European Parliament constituency)|South East England]]\n| status = \n| term_start = [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2 July 2019]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/elections-press-kit/0/key-dates-ahead |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=28 May 2019 |date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48365702|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=28 May 2019 |date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[Ray Finch]]\n| successor   = ''Constituency abolished''\n| term_end = 31 January 2020\n| parliament = European\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|02|28|df=yes}}<ref name=europarl-bio>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/197733/ROBERT_ROWLAND/home |title=Robert ROWLAND |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Bowdon, Greater Manchester]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Lisa Marie\n| relations = \n| children = 4\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Newcastle University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Robert Andrew Rowland''' is a British politician who has served as a [[Brexit Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for [[South East England (European Parliament constituency)|South East England]] from 2019 until the [[Brexit|United Kingdom's exit from the EU]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=The UK's European elections 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/crjeqkdevwvt/the-uks-european-elections-2019 |website=BBC News |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref> He was a member of the [[European Parliament Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs|Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs]]  and is a substitute on the [[European Parliament Committee on Industry, Research and Energy|Committee for Industry, Research and Energy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/197733/ROBERT_ROWLAND/history/9|title=9th parliamentary term {{!}} Robert ROWLAND {{!}} MEPs {{!}} European Parliament|website=www.europarl.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nRowland graduated from the University of Newcastle in 1988 with a BA (Hons)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://google.brand.edgar-online.com/efxapi/EFX_dll/EDGARpro.dll?FetchFilingHtmlSection1?SectionID=4178759-460851-467122&SessionID=j5B7eFiYveEvTG7 |website=Edgar Online |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> and began his career in the investment industry. He started at [[Lazard Fr\u00e8res|Lazard Asset Management]], and then became a fund manager with [[Odey Asset Management]] before  becoming a director at Soros Fund Management <ref>{{cite web |title= Mr Robert Andrew Rowland |url=https://register.fca.org.uk/ShPo_individualdetailsPage?id=003b000000LUwtiAAD |website=Financial Conduct Authority |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> He then moved back to  Lazard Asset Management in New York, after which he became a partner at Cheyne Capital Management (UK). Rowland is a director of the charity 'Tickets for Troops'. The charity distributes free tickets to members of the armed forces for a variety of sporting, musical and cultural events.<ref name=ticketsfortroops-directors>{{cite web |url=https://www.ticketsfortroops.org.uk/about-us/the-directors.aspx |title=The Directors |publisher=Tickets for Troops |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nRowland's first introduction to politics was while he was studying at the University of Newcastle. He stood for Deputy President of the Student's Union in 1987,<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle University Courier |url=http://courierarchive.ncl.ac.uk/sites/default/files/1987-01-29.pdf |website=Newcastle University Library Courier Archive |accessdate=26 December 2019 |page=3 |date=29 January 1987}}</ref> and on failing to win that position, the 5 March 1987 issue of the student newspaper, the Courier, reports that he stood unopposed for election for the Convener of the Disciplinary Committee, but lost by 335 votes to 395 against \"Re-open Nominations (R.O.N).\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle University Courier |url=http://courierarchive.ncl.ac.uk/sites/default/files/1987-03-05.pdf |website=Newcastle University Library Courier Archive |accessdate=26 December 2019 |page=2 |date=5 March 1987}}</ref> \n\nIn the 10 March 1988 edition of the Courier, he wrote a letter directed at what he dubbed \"the fascist left,\" and defending freedom of speech, and opposing the practice of providing \"no platform\" to speakers whose views were considered objectionable by some.<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle University Courier |url=http://courierarchive.ncl.ac.uk/sites/default/files/1988-03-10.pdf |website=Newcastle University Library Courier Archive |accessdate=26 December 2019 |page=4 |date=10 March 1988}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019 Rowland chose to return to politics, and at a european level, by standing as a candidate for the [[Brexit Party]]. Rowland gave his first major speech as a candidate at the Lakeside Hotel in Frimley, Surrey in May of that year, where he described opposition to Brexit as a potential \"coup against democracy\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/may/25/farage-brexit-party-remain|title=The energy behind Farage and his Brexit party leaves his rivals in the shadows|first=John|last=Harris|date=25 May 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nRowland was elected third on the Brexit Party list for the South East of England in the European Parliament elections in May 2019. He sat on the ECON (Economic and Monetary Affairs) committee in the European Parliament. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/unitedkingdom/en/european-elections/uk_meps/south_east_region.html|title=South East Region - 10 MEPs|website=www.europarl.europa.eu}}</ref> \n\nHe is a [[climate change sceptic]], saying in a debate on 23 October 2019:\n\n{{quote|There is, frankly, more credibility with the theories such as sunspots, the Milankovitch cycle and orbital variations than there is with anthropogenic warming<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web |title=Debates: Wednesday, 23 October 2019 - Strasbourg |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/CRE-9-2019-10-23-INT-3-270-0000_EN.html |website=European Parliament |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the same speech he said \"decarbonisation is deindustrialisation. It amounts to unilateral disarmament.\"<ref name=\"climate\" /> He argued that decarbonisation policies replace tax revenues generated from fossil fuels with subsidies to the detriment of the funding public services.\n\nWriting for the Daily Telegraph in September 2019, Rowland warned that the UK was giving up a claim to accumulated profits from the European Investment Bank in the proposed European Union withdrawal agreement. In the same article he also argued that large eurozone liabilities and the highly leveraged way that the Bank lends puts it at risk of a banking crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rowland |first1=Robert |title=Bunging the EU billions of pounds for free shows the toxic ineptitude at the heart of May's Brexit deal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/30/bunging-eu-billions-pounds-free-shows-toxic-ineptitude-heart/ |accessdate=20 December 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\nOn 9 July 2019, Rowland's Twitter activities received national attention when he tweeted at [[David Lammy]], MP: \"Lammy, you\u2019re first port of call should be the Chicago School of Economics. Complete 3 years and then you might understand 10% of what we all understand. Ignorance and race baiting is your signature tune.\" Twitter users were quick to point out that he had made a grammar error; that the Chicago School of Economics is not an actual university, but a school of thought; and that American degrees would in any case require 4 years, not 3. David Lammy also pointed out that he had, in fact, attended Harvard University.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit Party MEP tried to come for David Lammy\u2019s education and he was the one who got schooled |url=https://www.indy100.com/article/brexit-party-mep-david-lammy-robert-rowland-twitter-university-chicago-8998641 |accessdate=26 November 2019 |work=The Independent |date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, on 10 July 2019, Rowland tweeted  \"We are behind all our fisherman and the restoration of sovereignty over our waters. 200 miles of exclusion zone with any foreign fishing vessel given the same treatment as the [[ARA General Belgrano|Belgrano]]! Well done June. We are 110% behind you and will ensure you give \u2018em hell on committee.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Rowland Brexit SE Twitter|URL=https://twitter.com/RowlandBrexitSE|website=Twitter|accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>  His threat to sink foreign civilian fishing vessels was widely shared and criticised on social media.<ref name=guardian-20190712>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/12/brexit-party-mep-criticised-over-belgrano-twitter-comments |title=Brexit party MEP called for EU fishing vessels to be 'sunk like Belgrano' |last=Rankin |first=Jennifer |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 July 2019 |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2019, he again received media attention when an exchange with Green Party MEP [[Molly Scott Cato]] in the European Parliament was broadcast. Rowland asked what experience Scott Cato had to allow her to comment on the economic aspects of Brexit, as he said she had no background in economics, nor even a degree. In reality, as highlighted by Scott Cato, she is a Professor of Economics at the  University of Roehampton.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jankowicz |first1=Mia |title=Brexit Party MEP makes himself laughing stock in EU parliament challenge |url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/robert-rowland-eu-parliament-molly-scott-cato-1-6395124 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |work=The New European |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRowland is married with three sons and one daughter.<ref name=ticketsfortroops-directors/>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{Brexit Party}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rowland, Robert}}\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-MEP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Rowland"}
{"title_page": "Michael Platt (financier)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Michael Platt\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Michael Edward Platt\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|12|12|df=yes}}<ref name=\"octafinance\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], England\n| residence          = [[Jersey]]\n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[London School of Economics]]\n| occupation         = Investor and [[fund manager]]\n| known_for          = Co-founding [[BlueCrest Capital Management]]\n| salary             = \n| net_worth          = {{increase}} \u00a36.1 billion <small>(Sunday Times Rich List, 2019)</small> <br>\n[[US$]]8 billion <small>(October 2019)</small><ref name=\"Forbes: The World's Billionaires\">{{cite web|title=Forbes profile: Michael Platt|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/michael-platt/|website=Forbes|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n| title              = CEO, BlueCrest Capital Management\n| website            = http://www.bluecrestcapital.com/\n}}\n\n'''Michael Edward Platt''' (born 12 December 1968)<ref name=\"octafinance\"/> is a British billionaire [[Hedge fund|hedge fund manager]]. He is the co-founder and [[Chief executive officer|managing director]] of [[BlueCrest Capital Management]], Europe's third-largest hedge-fund firm<ref name=\"Bloomberg3\">{{cite web|last1=Westbrook|first1=Jesse|title=Man Who Said No to Soros Builds BlueCrest Into Empire|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-20/man-who-said-no-to-soros-builds-bluecrest-into-empire.html|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=27 August 2014|date=20 December 2013}}</ref> which he co-founded in 2000.\n\nHe is Britain's wealthiest hedge fund manager according to the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'', with an estimated wealth of \u00a36.1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eastoncaller.com/britains-wealthiest-hedge-fund-managers-are-revealed-in-mostly-male-sunday-times-rich-list/104684/|title=Britain\u2018s wealthiest hedge fund managers are revealed in mostly-male Sunday Times Rich List \u2013 Easton Caller|language=en-US|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sunday-times-rich-list-2019-profiles-21-50-richard-branson-salma-hayek-lmrpbmkb9|title=Rich List 2019: profiles 21-50=, featuring Richard Branson and Salma Hayek|work=The Sunday Times|date=12 May 2019|access-date=16 July 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> \n\n==Early life and education==\nPlatt was born in [[Preston, Lancashire]], England in 1968. His father taught civil engineering at the University of Manchester. His mother was a university administrator. His grandmother, whom he has described as \"a serious equity trader,\" introduced him to investment. She \"helped him buy stock in trust savings banks that were selling shares to the public.\" At 14, he invested \u00a3500 in a shipping line, Common Brothers, that soon tripled in price.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbreaker.com/2010/01/bluecrest-capital-founder-turned-on-to-trading-by-grandmother/|title=BlueCrest Capital Founder Turned On To Trading By Grandmother|first=Bess|last=Levin|publisher=}}</ref> Some of his first investments were in Britain's newly privatised utilities.<ref name=\"moneyweek.com\">{{cite web|url=https://moneyweek.com/the-worlds-greatest-investors-michael-platt/|title=The world's greatest investors: Michael Platt |date=28 July 2017|work=Money Week}}</ref>\n\nHe studied Civil Engineering at [[Imperial College London]]. After a year, he switched to Mathematics and Economics at the [[London School of Economics]], from which he graduated in 1991.<ref name=\"Businessweek1\">{{cite web|last1=Steward|first1=Martin|title=Company Overview of BlueCrest Capital Management (UK) LLP|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=8819651&privcapId=4663730|website=Businessweek|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Investment career==\n===Early career===\nPlatt started in the City after his grandmother gave him some shares in which to invest and he discovered he had a talent for investing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levin|first=Bess|url=http://dealbreaker.com/2010/01/bluecrest-capital-founder-turned-on-to-trading-by-grandmother|title=BlueCrest Capital Founder Turned On To Trading By Grandmother|publisher=Dealbreaker|date=14 April 2012|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"octafinance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.octafinance.com/michael-platt|title=Michael Platt profile|website=Octafinance.com|date=12 December 1968|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Godfrey Barker|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/how-mike-platt-and-joe-la-placa-took-over-the-contemporary-art-world-6741967.html|title=How Mike Platt and Joe La Placa took over the contemporary art world|website=Standard.co.uk|date=18 March 2010|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[JP Morgan]] in 1991. Platt assumed responsibility for developing JP Morgan's swaps and options trading business in April 1992, and in April 1996, became the head of trading for all swaps products relating to the 11 founding nations of the European single currency. In 2000 Platt co-founded BlueCrest Capital Management LLP, with [[William Reeves (finance)|William Reeves]].<ref name=\"London Evening Standard1\">{{cite web|last1=Barker|first1=Godfrey|title=How Mike Platt and Joe La Placa took over the contemporary art world|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/how-mike-platt-and-joe-la-placa-took-over-the-contemporary-art-world-6741967.html|website=Standard|publisher=Evening Standard|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Businessweek1\"/>\n\n===BlueCrest Capital===\n\nDiscerning in August 2007 that \u201ca stock market crash lay ahead,\u201d Platt \u201csold his bank shares, and bought \u2018safe\u2019 sovereign bonds,\u201d and thus \u201cavoided the worst of the financial crisis, and profited from the resulting 'flight to quality' and plunge in interest rates.\u201d<ref name=\"moneyweek.com\"/>\n\nAs of 2014, BlueCrest was Europe's fourth largest hedge fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/platt-s--50-billion-bluecrest-dream-deferred-as-investors-leave/41097962|title=Platt\u2019s $50 Billion BlueCrest Dream Deferred as Investors Leave|publisher=}}</ref> In that year, it managed over \u00a330 billion and employed 350 people.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|last1=Vardi|first1=Nathan|title=The 40 Highest-Earning Hedge Fund Managers|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/mdg45ghlg/michael-platt-2/|website=Forbes|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=27 August 2014|date=Jan 2012}}</ref> BlueCrest initially focused on trading interest rates and using computer algorithms to capture trends in bonds and commodities.\n\nIn 2013 it expanded into trading equity to compete with Millennium Management LLC and SAC Capital Advisors LLP.<ref name=\"Bloomberg3\"/>\n\nIn 2011, [[George Soros]] decided to stop managing money for outside clients and turn his hedge-fund firm into a family office. Soros spoke to Platt, asking him to take on more than $1 billion for a 0.5 percent management fee and a 10 percent performance fee. Platt reportedly declined the offer, saying plenty of investors were willing to pay BlueCrest 2-and-20, the industry standard fee structure.<ref name=\"Bloomberg2\">{{cite web|last1=Westbrook|first1=Jesse|title=Man Who Said No to Soros Builds BlueCrest Into Empire|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-20/man-who-said-no-to-soros-builds-bluecrest-into-empire.html|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Platt discussed the crisis in the Eurozone, attributing it to \"the cultural and political divide\" between north and south. \"The reality is that there is no willingness within the Eurozone to share wealth,\" he said. \"In the United States, if California is having a really difficult time, the rest of the United States will send money to California. This is not the case in Europe.\" He further maintained that Europe's problem was that \"almost every part of it has gone wrong now. The banks are undercapitalized\u2026If banks were hedge funds, and you mark them to market properly, I would say that probably most of them are insolvent.\" By contrast, he was relatively positive about the U.S. and Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-platt-bluecrest-capital-bloomberg-tv-2011-12?r=US&IR=T&IR=T|title=Hedge Fund Titan Michael Platt Reveals The Three Things He Won't Touch|work=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, BlueCrest invested $50 million in [[Meredith Whitney]]'s hedge fund, Kenbelle Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/meredith-whitney-shuts-her-hedge-fund-1433976677|title=Meredith Whitney Shuts Her Hedge Fund|first1=Rob|last1=Copeland|first2=Gregory|last2=Zuckerman|date=10 June 2015|publisher=|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>  In October of that year, BlueCrest made a redemption request, but while Kenbelle said it would comply, no repayment was forthcoming. The next year, BlueCrest sued in Bermuda to get its money back from the firm.  In 2015, Whitney closed up shop and paid back all her investors, including BlueCrest.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bizjournals.com/bizwomen/news/latest-news/2014/12/meredith-whitneys-biggest-investor-doesnt-just.html|title=Latest news|date=2014 |website=www.bizjournals.com}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbreaker.com/2015/06/meredith-whitney-is-returning-to-her-roots/|title=Meredith Whitney Is Returning To Her Roots|first=Bess|last=Levin|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Platt announced that BlueCrest would return $7 billion for outside investors, take no outside money in the future, and become a private partnership.<ref name=\"Forbes_20151201\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stevenson|first1=Alexandra|last2=Goldstein|first2=Matthew|title=BlueCrest to Close Hedge Fund and Refund Outside Investors|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/02/business/dealbook/bluecrest-capital-to-return-money-to-outside-investors.html|website=nytimes.com|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=8 October 2016|date=1 December 2015}}</ref> In his letter to investors explaining the change, Platt explained that \"Recent developments in the industry, including, among other things, downward pressure on fee levels, the increasing cost of hiring the best portfolio management talent and the difficulty in tailoring investment products to meet the individual needs and constraints of a large number of diverse investors, have all significantly reduced industry profitability and flexibility.\" Consequently \"BlueCrest believes that a transition to a Private Investment Partnership model is now appropriate for the business.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/michael-platts-bluecrest-to-return-outside-money-2015-12|title=A hedge fund that was once one of the world's largest is now returning money to investors|first=Julia La|last=Roche|date=2 December 2015|website=Business Insider Australia|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n \nIn 2016, BlueCrest had a profit of almost 50 percent; in 2017, Platt \"led his private investment firm to a 54 percent gain.\" This contrasted with \"mediocre returns at some of the largest hedge funds in the world,\" noted Bloomberg News.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-18/puerto-rico-battles-short-sighted-hedge-funds |title=Puerto Rico Battles Shortsighted Hedge Funds |work=Bloomberg |date=18 July 2018}}</ref> In 2018, the ''Sunday Times'' named Platt \"the richest hedge fund manager in the City.\" During the year, his net wealth had grown by 25 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hedgeweek.com/2018/05/11/264122/michael-platt-tops-sunday-times-hedge-fund-manager-rich-list|title=Michael Platt tops Sunday Times hedge fund manager rich list|author=|date=11 May 2018|website=Hedgeweek|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> In March 2019, he was named one of the highest-earning hedge fund managers and traders by ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2019/03/20/the-highest-earning-hedge-fund-managers-and-traders/|title=The Highest-Earning Hedge Fund Managers And Traders|first=Nathan|last=Vardi|date=|website=Forbes|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Strategy ===\n \nIn July 2017, Platt's investment strategy was described as follows: \u201cPlatt splits BlueCrest\u2019s assets between systematic strategies (based on pattern-spotting computer algorithms) and discretionary (human-driven) trades. The systematic trades are generally trend-following strategies \u2013 basically, buying assets that are going up, and selling ones that are falling. He delegates the day-to-day management to his traders, but retains overall control. He believes in aggressive stop losses \u2013 he will cut traders\u2019 allocations drastically if they lose as little as 3% of their capital, but will also lift allocations to winning trades.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moneyweek.com/470515/the-worlds-greatest-investors-michael-platt/|title=The world\u2019s greatest investors: Michael Platt|author=|date=28 July 2017|website=MoneyWeek|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his first live television interview, given to Bloomberg on 15 December 2011, Platt said that there are \u201cthree things he won't touch \u2013 exposure to banks, peripheral debt risk, and illiquid investments.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/michael-platt-bluecrest-capital-bloomberg-tv-2011-12|title=Hedge Fund Titan Michael Platt Reveals The Three Things He Won't Touch|first=Julia La|last=Roche|date=|website=Business Insider|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAsked how he finds \u201ctalented traders\u201d to employ, he has said that he seeks out \u201csomeone who understands an edge.\u201d For example, \u201cI look for the type of guy in London who gets up at seven o\u2019clock on Sunday morning when his kids are still in bed and logs on to a poker site so that he can pick off the US drunks coming home on Saturday night.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldtopinvestors.com/michael-platt-invests-his-own-money/|title=Michael Platt invests his own money \u2022 World Top Investors|author=|date=28 March 2018|website=worldtopinvestors.com|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>  There are at least three other things he looks for in traders: first, \u201c[a]n understanding that the market is always right,\u201d so that in when the market  is stress, value is irrelevant; second, \u201c[p]aranoia,\u201d which can lead them \u201cto hedge their winning trades\u201d and help them to \u201cmanage when they have losing positions\u201d; third, an ability to admit when one is wrong.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.topsteptrader.com/michael-platt-training-traders|title=Billionaire Hedge Fund Manager: What I Look for in My Traders|first=|last=TopstepTrader|date=|website=blog.topsteptrader.com|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, he moved from London to [[Geneva]], Switzerland to avoid increased regulation and for \"better staffing options\". In 2014, it was reported that he had relocated to [[Jersey]], along with his hedge fund, which was moving from nearby [[Guernsey]], for tax purposes.<ref name=\"Bloomberg LP\">{{cite news|last1=Fortado|first1=Lindsay|title=BlueCrest\u2019s Founder Platt Said to Move to Jersey From Geneva|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-12-10/bluecrests-founder-platt-said-to-move-to-jersey-from-geneva|accessdate=2 March 2017|work=Bloomberg LP|date=10 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes_20151201\">{{cite news|last1=Vardi|first1=Nathan|title=Billionaire Michael Platt Closes His BlueCrest Hedge Fund|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2015/12/01/billionaire-michael-platt-closes-his-bluecrest-hedge-fund/#4e7a3a28622f|accessdate=2 March 2017|work=Forbes|date=1 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.advfn.com/newspaper/azeez-mustapha/36646/michael-platt-one-of-the-most-effective-risk-managers|title=Michael Platt: One of the Most Effective Risk Managers|website=Uk.advfn.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a notable art collector having built a contemporary art collection not by shopping for pictures, but by commissioning them from well-known artists. He has a private showroom in the crypt of a deconsecrated church at One Marylebone, which displays a selection of art by, among others, taxidermist [[Polly Morgan (taxidermist)|Polly Morgan]], the Turner Prize-winning sculptor and installation artist [[Keith Tyson]] and [[Reece Jones (artist)|Reece Jones]] \"an artist who works mainly in charcoal\". <ref name=\"London Evening Standard1\"/>\n\nPlatt appeared as \"himself\" on Showtime's series ''Billions'' in episode 1, Season 3.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/25/arts/television/billions-season-3-premiere-recap-tie-goes-to-the-runner.html|title=\u2018Billions\u2019 Season 3 Premiere: The Next Big Thing|date=25 March 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Platt, Michael}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:English art collectors]]\n[[Category:English billionaires]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English investors]]\n[[Category:English stock traders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Preston, Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Stock and commodity market managers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Michael Platt\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Michael Edward Platt\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|12|12|df=yes}}<ref name=\"octafinance\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], England\n| residence          = [[Jersey]]\n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[London School of Economics]]\n| occupation         = Investor and [[fund manager]]\n| known_for          = Co-founding [[BlueCrest Capital Management]]\n| salary             = \n| net_worth          = {{increase}} \u00a36.1 billion <small>(Sunday Times Rich List, 2019)</small> <br>\n[[US$]]8 billion <small>(October 2019)</small><ref name=\"Forbes: The World's Billionaires\">{{cite web|title=Forbes profile: Michael Platt|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/michael-platt/|website=Forbes|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n| title              = CEO, BlueCrest Capital Management\n| website            = http://www.bluecrestcapital.com/\n}}\n\n'''Michael Edward Platt''' (born 12 December 1968)<ref name=\"octafinance\"/> is a British billionaire [[Hedge fund|hedge fund manager]]. He is the co-founder and [[Chief executive officer|managing director]] of [[BlueCrest Capital Management]], Europe's third-largest hedge-fund firm<ref name=\"Bloomberg3\">{{cite web|last1=Westbrook|first1=Jesse|title=Man Who Said No to Soros Builds BlueCrest Into Empire|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-20/man-who-said-no-to-soros-builds-bluecrest-into-empire.html|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=27 August 2014|date=20 December 2013}}</ref> which he co-founded in 2000.\n\nHe is Britain's wealthiest hedge fund manager according to the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'', with an estimated wealth of \u00a36.1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eastoncaller.com/britains-wealthiest-hedge-fund-managers-are-revealed-in-mostly-male-sunday-times-rich-list/104684/|title=Britain\u2018s wealthiest hedge fund managers are revealed in mostly-male Sunday Times Rich List \u2013 Easton Caller|language=en-US|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sunday-times-rich-list-2019-profiles-21-50-richard-branson-salma-hayek-lmrpbmkb9|title=Rich List 2019: profiles 21-50=, featuring Richard Branson and Salma Hayek|work=The Sunday Times|date=12 May 2019|access-date=16 July 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> \n\n==Early life and education==\nPlatt was born in [[Preston, Lancashire]], England in 1968. His father taught civil engineering at the University of Manchester. His mother was a university administrator. His grandmother, whom he has described as \"a serious equity trader,\" introduced him to investment. She \"helped him buy stock in trust savings banks that were selling shares to the public.\" At 14, he invested \u00a3500 in a shipping line, Common Brothers, that soon tripled in price.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbreaker.com/2010/01/bluecrest-capital-founder-turned-on-to-trading-by-grandmother/|title=BlueCrest Capital Founder Turned On To Trading By Grandmother|first=Bess|last=Levin|publisher=}}</ref> Some of his first investments were in Britain's newly privatised utilities.<ref name=\"moneyweek.com\">{{cite web|url=https://moneyweek.com/the-worlds-greatest-investors-michael-platt/|title=The world's greatest investors: Michael Platt |date=28 July 2017|work=Money Week}}</ref>\n\nHe studied Civil Engineering at [[Imperial College London]]. After a year, he switched to Mathematics and Economics at the [[London School of Economics]], from which he graduated in 1991.<ref name=\"Businessweek1\">{{cite web|last1=Steward|first1=Martin|title=Company Overview of BlueCrest Capital Management (UK) LLP|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=8819651&privcapId=4663730|website=Businessweek|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Investment career==\n===Early career===\nPlatt started in the City after his grandmother gave him some shares in which to invest and he discovered he had a talent for investing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levin|first=Bess|url=http://dealbreaker.com/2010/01/bluecrest-capital-founder-turned-on-to-trading-by-grandmother|title=BlueCrest Capital Founder Turned On To Trading By Grandmother|publisher=Dealbreaker|date=14 April 2012|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"octafinance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.octafinance.com/michael-platt|title=Michael Platt profile|website=Octafinance.com|date=12 December 1968|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Godfrey Barker|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/how-mike-platt-and-joe-la-placa-took-over-the-contemporary-art-world-6741967.html|title=How Mike Platt and Joe La Placa took over the contemporary art world|website=Standard.co.uk|date=18 March 2010|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[JP Morgan]] in 1991. Platt assumed responsibility for developing JP Morgan's swaps and options trading business in April 1992, and in April 1996, became the head of trading for all swaps products relating to the 11 founding nations of the European single currency. In 2000 Platt co-founded BlueCrest Capital Management LLP, with [[William Reeves (finance)|William Reeves]].<ref name=\"London Evening Standard1\">{{cite web|last1=Barker|first1=Godfrey|title=How Mike Platt and Joe La Placa took over the contemporary art world|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/how-mike-platt-and-joe-la-placa-took-over-the-contemporary-art-world-6741967.html|website=Standard|publisher=Evening Standard|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Businessweek1\"/>\n\n===BlueCrest Capital===\n\nDiscerning in August 2007 that \u201ca stock market crash lay ahead,\u201d Platt \u201csold his bank shares, and bought \u2018safe\u2019 sovereign bonds,\u201d and thus \u201cavoided the worst of the financial crisis, and profited from the resulting 'flight to quality' and plunge in interest rates.\u201d<ref name=\"moneyweek.com\"/>\n\nAs of 2014, BlueCrest was Europe's fourth largest hedge fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/platt-s--50-billion-bluecrest-dream-deferred-as-investors-leave/41097962|title=Platt\u2019s $50 Billion BlueCrest Dream Deferred as Investors Leave|publisher=}}</ref> In that year, it managed over \u00a330 billion and employed 350 people.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|last1=Vardi|first1=Nathan|title=The 40 Highest-Earning Hedge Fund Managers|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/mdg45ghlg/michael-platt-2/|website=Forbes|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=27 August 2014|date=Jan 2012}}</ref> BlueCrest initially focused on trading interest rates and using computer algorithms to capture trends in bonds and commodities.\n\nIn 2013 it expanded into trading equity to compete with Millennium Management LLC and SAC Capital Advisors LLP.<ref name=\"Bloomberg3\"/>\n\nIn 2011, [[George Soros]] decided to stop managing money for outside clients and turn his hedge-fund firm into a family office. Soros spoke to Platt, asking him to take on more than $1 billion for a 0.5 percent management fee and a 10 percent performance fee. Platt reportedly declined the offer, saying plenty of investors were willing to pay BlueCrest 2-and-20, the industry standard fee structure.<ref name=\"Bloomberg2\">{{cite web|last1=Westbrook|first1=Jesse|title=Man Who Said No to Soros Builds BlueCrest Into Empire|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-20/man-who-said-no-to-soros-builds-bluecrest-into-empire.html|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Platt discussed the crisis in the Eurozone, attributing it to \"the cultural and political divide\" between north and south. \"The reality is that there is no willingness within the Eurozone to share wealth,\" he said. \"In the United States, if California is having a really difficult time, the rest of the United States will send money to California. This is not the case in Europe.\" He further maintained that Europe's problem was that \"almost every part of it has gone wrong now. The banks are undercapitalized\u2026If banks were hedge funds, and you mark them to market properly, I would say that probably most of them are insolvent.\" By contrast, he was relatively positive about the U.S. and Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-platt-bluecrest-capital-bloomberg-tv-2011-12?r=US&IR=T&IR=T|title=Hedge Fund Titan Michael Platt Reveals The Three Things He Won't Touch|work=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, BlueCrest invested $50 million in [[Meredith Whitney]]'s hedge fund, Kenbelle Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/meredith-whitney-shuts-her-hedge-fund-1433976677|title=Meredith Whitney Shuts Her Hedge Fund|first1=Rob|last1=Copeland|first2=Gregory|last2=Zuckerman|date=10 June 2015|publisher=|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>  In October of that year, BlueCrest made a redemption request, but while Kenbelle said it would comply, no repayment was forthcoming. The next year, BlueCrest sued in Bermuda to get its money back from the firm.  In 2015, Whitney closed up shop and paid back all her investors, including BlueCrest.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bizjournals.com/bizwomen/news/latest-news/2014/12/meredith-whitneys-biggest-investor-doesnt-just.html|title=Latest news|date=2014 |website=www.bizjournals.com}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbreaker.com/2015/06/meredith-whitney-is-returning-to-her-roots/|title=Meredith Whitney Is Returning To Her Roots|first=Bess|last=Levin|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Platt announced that BlueCrest would return $7 billion for outside investors, take no outside money in the future, and become a private partnership.<ref name=\"Forbes_20151201\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stevenson|first1=Alexandra|last2=Goldstein|first2=Matthew|title=BlueCrest to Close Hedge Fund and Refund Outside Investors|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/02/business/dealbook/bluecrest-capital-to-return-money-to-outside-investors.html|website=nytimes.com|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=8 October 2016|date=1 December 2015}}</ref> In his letter to investors explaining the change, Platt explained that \"Recent developments in the industry, including, among other things, downward pressure on fee levels, the increasing cost of hiring the best portfolio management talent and the difficulty in tailoring investment products to meet the individual needs and constraints of a large number of diverse investors, have all significantly reduced industry profitability and flexibility.\" Consequently \"BlueCrest believes that a transition to a Private Investment Partnership model is now appropriate for the business.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/michael-platts-bluecrest-to-return-outside-money-2015-12|title=A hedge fund that was once one of the world's largest is now returning money to investors|first=Julia La|last=Roche|date=2 December 2015|website=Business Insider Australia|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n \nIn 2016, BlueCrest had a profit of almost 50 percent; in 2017, Platt \"led his private investment firm to a 54 percent gain.\" This contrasted with \"mediocre returns at some of the largest hedge funds in the world,\" noted Bloomberg News.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-18/puerto-rico-battles-short-sighted-hedge-funds |title=Puerto Rico Battles Shortsighted Hedge Funds |work=Bloomberg |date=18 July 2018}}</ref> In 2018, the ''Sunday Times'' named Platt \"the richest hedge fund manager in the City.\" During the year, his net wealth had grown by 25 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hedgeweek.com/2018/05/11/264122/michael-platt-tops-sunday-times-hedge-fund-manager-rich-list|title=Michael Platt tops Sunday Times hedge fund manager rich list|author=|date=11 May 2018|website=Hedgeweek|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> In March 2019, he was named one of the highest-earning hedge fund managers and traders by ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2019/03/20/the-highest-earning-hedge-fund-managers-and-traders/|title=The Highest-Earning Hedge Fund Managers And Traders|first=Nathan|last=Vardi|date=|website=Forbes|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Strategy ===\n \nIn July 2017, Platt's investment strategy was described as follows: \u201cPlatt splits BlueCrest\u2019s assets between systematic strategies (based on pattern-spotting computer algorithms) and discretionary (human-driven) trades. The systematic trades are generally trend-following strategies \u2013 basically, buying assets that are going up, and selling ones that are falling. He delegates the day-to-day management to his traders, but retains overall control. He believes in aggressive stop losses \u2013 he will cut traders\u2019 allocations drastically if they lose as little as 3% of their capital, but will also lift allocations to winning trades.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moneyweek.com/470515/the-worlds-greatest-investors-michael-platt/|title=The world\u2019s greatest investors: Michael Platt|author=|date=28 July 2017|website=MoneyWeek|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his first live television interview, given to Bloomberg on 15 December 2011, Platt said that there are \u201cthree things he won't touch \u2013 exposure to banks, peripheral debt risk, and illiquid investments.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/michael-platt-bluecrest-capital-bloomberg-tv-2011-12|title=Hedge Fund Titan Michael Platt Reveals The Three Things He Won't Touch|first=Julia La|last=Roche|date=|website=Business Insider|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAsked how he finds \u201ctalented traders\u201d to employ, he has said that he seeks out \u201csomeone who understands an edge.\u201d For example, \u201cI look for the type of guy in London who gets up at seven o\u2019clock on Sunday morning when his kids are still in bed and logs on to a poker site so that he can pick off the US drunks coming home on Saturday night.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldtopinvestors.com/michael-platt-invests-his-own-money/|title=Michael Platt invests his own money \u2022 World Top Investors|author=|date=28 March 2018|website=worldtopinvestors.com|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>  There are at least three other things he looks for in traders: first, \u201c[a]n understanding that the market is always right,\u201d so that in when the market  is stress, value is irrelevant; second, \u201c[p]aranoia,\u201d which can lead them \u201cto hedge their winning trades\u201d and help them to \u201cmanage when they have losing positions\u201d; third, an ability to admit when one is wrong.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.topsteptrader.com/michael-platt-training-traders|title=Billionaire Hedge Fund Manager: What I Look for in My Traders|first=|last=TopstepTrader|date=|website=blog.topsteptrader.com|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, he moved from London to [[Geneva]], Switzerland to avoid increased regulation and for \"better staffing options\". In 2014, it was reported that he had relocated to [[Jersey]], along with his hedge fund, which was moving from nearby [[Guernsey]], for tax purposes.<ref name=\"Bloomberg LP\">{{cite news|last1=Fortado|first1=Lindsay|title=BlueCrest\u2019s Founder Platt Said to Move to Jersey From Geneva|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-12-10/bluecrests-founder-platt-said-to-move-to-jersey-from-geneva|accessdate=2 March 2017|work=Bloomberg LP|date=10 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes_20151201\">{{cite news|last1=Vardi|first1=Nathan|title=Billionaire Michael Platt Closes His BlueCrest Hedge Fund|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2015/12/01/billionaire-michael-platt-closes-his-bluecrest-hedge-fund/#4e7a3a28622f|accessdate=2 March 2017|work=Forbes|date=1 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.advfn.com/newspaper/azeez-mustapha/36646/michael-platt-one-of-the-most-effective-risk-managers|title=Michael Platt: One of the Most Effective Risk Managers|website=Uk.advfn.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a notable art collector having built a contemporary art collection not by shopping for pictures, but by commissioning them from well-known artists. He has a private showroom in the crypt of a deconsecrated church at One Marylebone, which displays a selection of art by, among others, taxidermist [[Polly Morgan (taxidermist)|Polly Morgan]], the Turner Prize-winning sculptor and installation artist [[Keith Tyson]] and [[Reece Jones (artist)|Reece Jones]] \"an artist who works mainly in charcoal\". <ref name=\"London Evening Standard1\"/>\n\nPlatt appeared as \"himself\" on Showtime's series ''Billions'' in episode 1, Season 3.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/25/arts/television/billions-season-3-premiere-recap-tie-goes-to-the-runner.html|title=\u2018Billions\u2019 Season 3 Premiere: The Next Big Thing|date=25 March 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Platt, Michael}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:English art collectors]]\n[[Category:English billionaires]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English investors]]\n[[Category:English stock traders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Preston, Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Stock and commodity market managers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Platt_(financier)"}
{"title_page": "Jonathan Ruffer", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Jonathan Ruffer\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Jonathan Garnier Ruffer\n{{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|08|17}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education =  [[Marlborough College]]<br/>[[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = City investor, art collector\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = GBP \u00a3380&nbsp;million<ref name=STRL>{{cite news|title=Sunday Times Rich List|work=The Sunday Times|issue=page 42|date=18 May 2014|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| spouse = Jane Sequeira\n| children = 1 daughter\n| parents = \n| relatives =\n}}\n'''Jonathan Ruffer''' [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (born 17 August 1951) is a British City investor, art collector and philanthropist.\n\n==Early life==\nJonathan Ruffer was born on 17 August 1951 in London, England, and lived from an early age in [[Stokesley]], North Yorkshire, England.<ref name=\"debretts\">[http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/3229/Jonathan-Garnier-RUFFER Jonathan Garnier Ruffer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426002916/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/3229/Jonathan-Garnier-RUFFER |date=26 April 2015 }}, ''[[Debrett's]]''</ref><ref name=\"yorkshirepost\">[http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/business/business-news/ruffer-llp-pays-member-of-firm-18m-1-7023126 Ruffer LLP pays member of firm \u00a318m], ''Yorkshire Post'', 28 December 2014</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tees-16705295 Millionaire Jonathan Ruffer pledges to tackle deprivation], [[BBC]], 25 January 2012</ref> He was educated at [[Marlborough College]], a [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] in [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]].<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He graduated from [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge|Sidney Sussex College]], a constituent college of the [[University of Cambridge]], in 1972.<ref name=\"debretts\"/><ref name=\"durham\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/st-johns.college/research/fellows/jonathanruffer/|title=St John's College : Jonathan Ruffer - Durham University|author=|date=|website=www.dur.ac.uk|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRuffer started as a stockbroker, before becoming a barrister.<ref name=STRL /> He is now a Bencher of the Middle Temple.  He worked in corporate finance for [[Schroders]], an accepting house bank.<ref name=\"durham\"/><ref name=\"bloombergbusiness\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=6958642&privcapId=32624876&previousCapId=10837322&previousTitle=Ruffer%20LLP Jonathan Ruffer], ''[[Bloomberg Business]]''</ref> He worked for Dunbar, a private bank,<ref name=\"managementtoday\">Philip Beresford, [http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/news/1318633%20 Britain's Top 100 Entrepreneurs 2014: No. 10 \u2013 Jonathan Ruffer, Ruffer Management: The investment entrepreneur is worth \u00a3380m.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074008/http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/news/1318633%20 |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''Management Today'', 26 October 2014</ref> from 1980 to 1985.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He was also on the board of directors of one of its subsidiaries, Dunbar Fund Management, from 1981 to 1985.<ref name=\"managementtoday\"/> He was then on the board of CFS (renamed Rathbone plc) from 1985 to 1994.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He was on the board of Odey Asset Management, founded by [[Crispin Odey]], from 1992 to 2005; Fuel Tech from 1994 to 1998; and Electric & General Investment Trust from 2001 to 2011.<ref name=\"debretts\"/>\n\nIn 1994, he co-founded Ruffer Investment Management Limited, an investment management firm with [[Robert Shirley, 14th Earl Ferrers]] and Jane Tufnell.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/><ref>Julia Rampen, [http://www.investmentweek.co.uk/investment-week/news/2338141/ruffer-co-founder-steps-down Ruffer co-founder steps down], ''Investment Week'', 4 April 2014</ref> The firm was renamed Ruffer LLP in 2004 and is now based at 80 Victoria Street in London.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruffer.co.uk/#contact|title=Investment Funds - Investment Management - London, Edinburgh, Guernsey - UK - Ruffer|author=|date=|website=www.ruffer.co.uk|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Ruffer was its chief executive officer from 1994 to 2012<ref name=\"debretts\"/> and has been its chairman since 2011.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> The firm managed \u00a315.4 billion on behalf of its clients in 2012\u20132013.<ref name=\"managementtoday\"/> In 2014, it had 199 employees,<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/> and additional offices in [[Edinburgh]] and Hong Kong.<ref name=\"katieholliday\">Katie Holliday, [http://www.investmentweek.co.uk/investment-week/news/2166947/jonathan-ruffer-steps-ruffer-investments Jonathan Ruffer steps back from Ruffer Investments], ''Investment Week'', 11 April 2012</ref>\n\nHe is a research fellow at [[St John's College, Durham]].<ref name=\"durham\"/> He has published articles in ''[[The Spectator]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/author/jonathan-ruffer/|title=Author: Jonathan Ruffer - The Spectator|author=|date=|website=The Spectator|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nRuffer credits [[William Rathbone VI]] as a source of inspiration for his philanthropy.<ref name=\"ftcastle\">A N Wilson, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/57d38f48-6421-11e4-8ade-00144feabdc0.html Man on a mission: Jonathan Ruffer and the Auckland Castle Trust], ''[[Financial Times]]'', 7 November 2014</ref> He believes nobody needs more than \u00a320&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/> However, he is critical of [[William Temple (bishop)|William Temple]]'s Christian socialism.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/>\n\nHe served as the chairman of the Good Shepherd Mission in [[Bethnal Green]] from 1998 to 2008.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He has also supported the [[Church Urban Fund]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tees-16705295|title=Millionaire Jonathan Ruffer pledges to tackle deprivation |work=BBC|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Auckland Castle Crop.jpg|thumb|right|[[Auckland Castle]] in [[Bishop Auckland]], County Durham.]]\nHe expressed an interest in reviving County Durham through philanthropy in 2012.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> That same year, he donated \u00a31&nbsp;million to the Durham Foundation.<ref name=\"thejournal\">[http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/jonathan-ruffer-donates-1m-donation-4403237 Jonathan Ruffer donates \u00a31m donation to Durham foundation], ''The Journal'', 7 September 2012</ref> A year later, in 2013, he donated \u00a315&nbsp;million to preserve [[Auckland Castle]], the historical palace of the [[Bishop of Durham]], through the Auckland Castle Trust,<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/><ref name=\"telegraphcharlesmoore\">Charles Moore, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/10062215/The-great-Auckland-Castle-rescue.html The great Auckland Castle rescue], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 18 May 2013</ref> of which he is the chair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aucklandcastle.org/the-trust|title=Auckland Castle|author=|date=|website=Auckland Castle|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"heritageexchange\">[http://www.heritageexchange.co.uk/content/jonathan-ruffer Heritage Exchange 2014: Jonathan Ruffer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415105037/http://www.heritageexchange.co.uk/content/jonathan-ruffer |date=15 April 2015 }}</ref> This included the preservation of 12 paintings by [[Francisco de Zurbar\u00e1n]], present in the palace since 1756.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/><ref name=\"heritageexchange\"/><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-12913686 Francisco Zurbaran paintings saved by \u00a315m donation], BBC, 31 March 2011</ref> In 2013, he donated \u00a318&nbsp;million to restore the Bishop's Palace and create a museum on the history of Christianity and faith in Britain, which had been expected to open in 2018.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/><ref name=\"telegraphcharlesmoore\"/> \n\nThe restoration project was completed in 2019 and the Castle was scheduled to re-open to visitors in November; <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/oct/25/auckland-castle-durham-to-open-after-restoration|title=Auckland Castle in Durham to open to public after \u00a312.4m restoration|publisher=the Guardian|date=25 October 2019|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Simpson|first=Harriet Agerholm, Emma|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51648556|title=The multimillionaire's plan to reinvent a town|date=2020-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-04|last2=Palumbo|first2=Daniele|language=en-GB}}</ref> three new restaurants for visitors were added, with one in operation by early November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tees-49663538|title=Auckland Castle to re-open after multimillion-pound restoration|publisher=BBC|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>   <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandproject.org/eat-and-shop/|title=Eat & shop|publisher=The Auckland Project|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> Nonetheless, the Scotland Wing still houses the offices of the Bishop of Durham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandproject.org/the-bishops-of-durham-through-time/|title=The Bishops of Durham Through Time|publisher=The Auckland Project|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> In 2019, he worked with Sotheby's James Macdonald (an expert on the Spanish school) to assemble a collection displayed at the Spanish Gallery.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gates|first=Anita|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/arts/private-sales-offer-art-for-a-few-eyes-only.html|title=Private Sales Offer Art for a Few Eyes Only|date=2018-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Ruffer donated the endowment to create [[Kynren]], a night show telling the history of England, in nearby [[Bishop Auckland]] to aid in wider regeneration.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2014-04-03/benefactor-plans-theme-park-for-bishop-auckland/ Benefactor plans theme park for Bishop Auckland], ITV, 3 April 2014</ref>\n\nHe has endowed the Jonathan Ruffer curatorial grants at [[The Art Fund]], which give \u00a375,000 to curators every year.<ref name=\"artfundgrants\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artfund.org/supporting-museums/jonathan-ruffer-curatorial-grants|title=Jonathan Ruffer curatorial grants|first=Art|last=Fund|date=|website=artfund.org|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Art collection==\nRuffer collects Spanish old masters.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/> He also owns paintings by [[Thomas Gainsborough]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Isaac Henrique Sequeira (Gainsborough).jpg|thumb|[[Isaac Henrique Sequeira]], by [[Thomas Gainsborough]].<br>[[Museo del Prado]], Madrid.]]\nRuffer is married to Jane Sequeira, a doctor, and palliative care specialist.<ref name=\"durham\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/8979806.Zurbarans____trustees_revealed_by_owner/|title=Zurbarans\u2019 trustees revealed by owner|author=|date=|website=The Northern Echo|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> They have a daughter.<ref name=\"durham\"/> She is a descendant of [[Isaac Henrique Sequeira]] (1738-1816), a Portuguese Jewish doctor, who was painted by [[Thomas Gainsborough]], one of his patients, and that oil painting now hangs in Madrid's [[Museo del Prado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2011/04/24/cultura/1303596003_850215.html|title=Reportaje - El salvador de los 'zurbar\u00e1n'|first=Ediciones El|last=Pa\u00eds|date=24 April 2011|publisher=|accessdate=5 February 2018|via=elpais.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/art-work/isaac-henrique-sequeira/8a1936f6-a7d8-4c00-b9a5-6bb1a99df911|title=Isaac Henrique Sequeira - The Collection - Museo Nacional del Prado|author=|date=|website=www.museodelprado.es|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn Anglican,<ref name=\"telegraphcharlesmoore\"/> he has been described by the ''[[Financial Times]]'' as \"a committed evangelical Christian\"<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/> and ''[[The Yorkshire Post]]'' as \"a devout Christian.\"<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/> He is a member of the [[Athenaeum Club, London|Athenaeum Club]] and the [[Beefsteak Club]].<ref name=\"debretts\"/> As of 2014, he had an estimated wealth of \u00a3380&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''The Big Shots'' (1977).\n*''Babel, the Breaking of the Banks'' (2009)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandcastle.org Auckland Castle]\n* [http://elevenarches.org/ Kynren at Eleven Arches]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruffer, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:People from Hambleton District]]\n[[Category:Art collectors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Durham]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British corporate directors]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Academics of Durham University]]\n[[Category:Schroders people]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Jonathan Ruffer\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Jonathan Garnier Ruffer\n{{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|08|17}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education =  [[Marlborough College]]<br/>[[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = City investor, art collector\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = GBP \u00a3380&nbsp;million<ref name=STRL>{{cite news|title=Sunday Times Rich List|work=The Sunday Times|issue=page 42|date=18 May 2014|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| spouse = Jane Sequeira\n| children = 1 daughter\n| parents = \n| relatives =\n}}\n'''Jonathan Ruffer''' [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (born 17 August 1951) is a British City investor, art collector and philanthropist.\n\n==Early life==\nJonathan Ruffer was born on 17 August 1951 in London, England, and lived from an early age in [[Stokesley]], North Yorkshire, England.<ref name=\"debretts\">[http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/3229/Jonathan-Garnier-RUFFER Jonathan Garnier Ruffer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426002916/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/3229/Jonathan-Garnier-RUFFER |date=26 April 2015 }}, ''[[Debrett's]]''</ref><ref name=\"yorkshirepost\">[http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/business/business-news/ruffer-llp-pays-member-of-firm-18m-1-7023126 Ruffer LLP pays member of firm \u00a318m], ''Yorkshire Post'', 28 December 2014</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tees-16705295 Millionaire Jonathan Ruffer pledges to tackle deprivation], [[BBC]], 25 January 2012</ref> He was educated at [[Marlborough College]], a [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] in [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]].<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He graduated from [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge|Sidney Sussex College]], a constituent college of the [[University of Cambridge]], in 1972.<ref name=\"debretts\"/><ref name=\"durham\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/st-johns.college/research/fellows/jonathanruffer/|title=St John's College : Jonathan Ruffer - Durham University|author=|date=|website=www.dur.ac.uk|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRuffer started as a stockbroker, before becoming a barrister.<ref name=STRL /> He is now a Bencher of the Middle Temple.  He worked in corporate finance for [[Schroders]], an accepting house bank.<ref name=\"durham\"/><ref name=\"bloombergbusiness\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=6958642&privcapId=32624876&previousCapId=10837322&previousTitle=Ruffer%20LLP Jonathan Ruffer], ''[[Bloomberg Business]]''</ref> He worked for Dunbar, a private bank,<ref name=\"managementtoday\">Philip Beresford, [http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/news/1318633%20 Britain's Top 100 Entrepreneurs 2014: No. 10 \u2013 Jonathan Ruffer, Ruffer Management: The investment entrepreneur is worth \u00a3380m.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074008/http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/news/1318633%20 |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''Management Today'', 26 October 2014</ref> from 1980 to 1985.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He was also on the board of directors of one of its subsidiaries, Dunbar Fund Management, from 1981 to 1985.<ref name=\"managementtoday\"/> He was then on the board of CFS (renamed Rathbone plc) from 1985 to 1994.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He was on the board of Odey Asset Management, founded by [[Crispin Odey]], from 1992 to 2005; Fuel Tech from 1994 to 1998; and Electric & General Investment Trust from 2001 to 2011.<ref name=\"debretts\"/>\n\nIn 1994, he co-founded Ruffer Investment Management Limited, an investment management firm with [[Robert Shirley, 14th Earl Ferrers]] and Jane Tufnell.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/><ref>Julia Rampen, [http://www.investmentweek.co.uk/investment-week/news/2338141/ruffer-co-founder-steps-down Ruffer co-founder steps down], ''Investment Week'', 4 April 2014</ref> The firm was renamed Ruffer LLP in 2004 and is now based at 80 Victoria Street in London.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruffer.co.uk/#contact|title=Investment Funds - Investment Management - London, Edinburgh, Guernsey - UK - Ruffer|author=|date=|website=www.ruffer.co.uk|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Ruffer was its chief executive officer from 1994 to 2012<ref name=\"debretts\"/> and has been its chairman since 2011.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> The firm managed \u00a315.4 billion on behalf of its clients in 2012\u20132013.<ref name=\"managementtoday\"/> In 2014, it had 199 employees,<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/> and additional offices in [[Edinburgh]] and Hong Kong.<ref name=\"katieholliday\">Katie Holliday, [http://www.investmentweek.co.uk/investment-week/news/2166947/jonathan-ruffer-steps-ruffer-investments Jonathan Ruffer steps back from Ruffer Investments], ''Investment Week'', 11 April 2012</ref>\n\nHe is a research fellow at [[St John's College, Durham]].<ref name=\"durham\"/> He has published articles in ''[[The Spectator]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/author/jonathan-ruffer/|title=Author: Jonathan Ruffer - The Spectator|author=|date=|website=The Spectator|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nRuffer credits [[William Rathbone VI]] as a source of inspiration for his philanthropy.<ref name=\"ftcastle\">A N Wilson, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/57d38f48-6421-11e4-8ade-00144feabdc0.html Man on a mission: Jonathan Ruffer and the Auckland Castle Trust], ''[[Financial Times]]'', 7 November 2014</ref> He believes nobody needs more than \u00a320&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/> However, he is critical of [[William Temple (bishop)|William Temple]]'s Christian socialism.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/>\n\nHe served as the chairman of the Good Shepherd Mission in [[Bethnal Green]] from 1998 to 2008.<ref name=\"debretts\"/> He has also supported the [[Church Urban Fund]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tees-16705295|title=Millionaire Jonathan Ruffer pledges to tackle deprivation |work=BBC|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Auckland Castle Crop.jpg|thumb|right|[[Auckland Castle]] in [[Bishop Auckland]], County Durham.]]\nHe expressed an interest in reviving County Durham through philanthropy in 2012.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> That same year, he donated \u00a31&nbsp;million to the Durham Foundation.<ref name=\"thejournal\">[http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/jonathan-ruffer-donates-1m-donation-4403237 Jonathan Ruffer donates \u00a31m donation to Durham foundation], ''The Journal'', 7 September 2012</ref> A year later, in 2013, he donated \u00a315&nbsp;million to preserve [[Auckland Castle]], the historical palace of the [[Bishop of Durham]], through the Auckland Castle Trust,<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/><ref name=\"telegraphcharlesmoore\">Charles Moore, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/10062215/The-great-Auckland-Castle-rescue.html The great Auckland Castle rescue], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 18 May 2013</ref> of which he is the chair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aucklandcastle.org/the-trust|title=Auckland Castle|author=|date=|website=Auckland Castle|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"heritageexchange\">[http://www.heritageexchange.co.uk/content/jonathan-ruffer Heritage Exchange 2014: Jonathan Ruffer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415105037/http://www.heritageexchange.co.uk/content/jonathan-ruffer |date=15 April 2015 }}</ref> This included the preservation of 12 paintings by [[Francisco de Zurbar\u00e1n]], present in the palace since 1756.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/><ref name=\"heritageexchange\"/><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-12913686 Francisco Zurbaran paintings saved by \u00a315m donation], BBC, 31 March 2011</ref> In 2013, he donated \u00a318&nbsp;million to restore the Bishop's Palace and create a museum on the history of Christianity and faith in Britain, which had been expected to open in 2018.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/><ref name=\"telegraphcharlesmoore\"/> \n\nThe restoration project was completed in 2019 and the Castle was scheduled to re-open to visitors in November; <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/oct/25/auckland-castle-durham-to-open-after-restoration|title=Auckland Castle in Durham to open to public after \u00a312.4m restoration|publisher=the Guardian|date=25 October 2019|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Simpson|first=Harriet Agerholm, Emma|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51648556|title=The multimillionaire's plan to reinvent a town|date=2020-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-04|last2=Palumbo|first2=Daniele|language=en-GB}}</ref> three new restaurants for visitors were added, with one in operation by early November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tees-49663538|title=Auckland Castle to re-open after multimillion-pound restoration|publisher=BBC|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>   <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandproject.org/eat-and-shop/|title=Eat & shop|publisher=The Auckland Project|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> Nonetheless, the Scotland Wing still houses the offices of the Bishop of Durham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandproject.org/the-bishops-of-durham-through-time/|title=The Bishops of Durham Through Time|publisher=The Auckland Project|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> In 2019, he worked with Sotheby's James Macdonald (an expert on the Spanish school) to assemble a collection displayed at the Spanish Gallery.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gates|first=Anita|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/arts/private-sales-offer-art-for-a-few-eyes-only.html|title=Private Sales Offer Art for a Few Eyes Only|date=2018-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Ruffer donated the endowment to create [[Kynren]], a night show telling the history of England, in nearby [[Bishop Auckland]] to aid in wider regeneration.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2014-04-03/benefactor-plans-theme-park-for-bishop-auckland/ Benefactor plans theme park for Bishop Auckland], ITV, 3 April 2014</ref>\n\nHe has endowed the Jonathan Ruffer curatorial grants at [[The Art Fund]], which give \u00a375,000 to curators every year.<ref name=\"artfundgrants\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artfund.org/supporting-museums/jonathan-ruffer-curatorial-grants|title=Jonathan Ruffer curatorial grants|first=Art|last=Fund|date=|website=artfund.org|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Art collection==\nRuffer collects Spanish old masters.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/> He also owns paintings by [[Thomas Gainsborough]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Isaac Henrique Sequeira (Gainsborough).jpg|thumb|[[Isaac Henrique Sequeira]], by [[Thomas Gainsborough]].<br>[[Museo del Prado]], Madrid.]]\nRuffer is married to Jane Sequeira, a doctor, and palliative care specialist.<ref name=\"durham\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/8979806.Zurbarans____trustees_revealed_by_owner/|title=Zurbarans\u2019 trustees revealed by owner|author=|date=|website=The Northern Echo|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> They have a daughter.<ref name=\"durham\"/> She is a descendant of [[Isaac Henrique Sequeira]] (1738-1816), a Portuguese Jewish doctor, who was painted by [[Thomas Gainsborough]], one of his patients, and that oil painting now hangs in Madrid's [[Museo del Prado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2011/04/24/cultura/1303596003_850215.html|title=Reportaje - El salvador de los 'zurbar\u00e1n'|first=Ediciones El|last=Pa\u00eds|date=24 April 2011|publisher=|accessdate=5 February 2018|via=elpais.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/art-work/isaac-henrique-sequeira/8a1936f6-a7d8-4c00-b9a5-6bb1a99df911|title=Isaac Henrique Sequeira - The Collection - Museo Nacional del Prado|author=|date=|website=www.museodelprado.es|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn Anglican,<ref name=\"telegraphcharlesmoore\"/> he has been described by the ''[[Financial Times]]'' as \"a committed evangelical Christian\"<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/> and ''[[The Yorkshire Post]]'' as \"a devout Christian.\"<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\"/> He is a member of the [[Athenaeum Club, London|Athenaeum Club]] and the [[Beefsteak Club]].<ref name=\"debretts\"/> As of 2014, he had an estimated wealth of \u00a3380&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"ftcastle\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''The Big Shots'' (1977).\n*''Babel, the Breaking of the Banks'' (2009)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandcastle.org Auckland Castle]\n* [http://elevenarches.org/ Kynren at Eleven Arches]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruffer, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:People from Hambleton District]]\n[[Category:Art collectors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Durham]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:British corporate directors]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Academics of Durham University]]\n[[Category:Schroders people]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Ruffer"}
{"title_page": "Stanley Fink, Baron Fink", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Lord Fink\n| honorific-suffix ={{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FCA}}\n| image              = Official portrait of Lord Fink crop 2.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| birth_name         = Stanley Fink\n|office7         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start7       = 18 January 2011<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end7       =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth-date and age|15 September 1957}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manchester]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = London\n| nationality        = British\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = [[Financial services]]\n| education          = [[Manchester Grammar School]],<br/>[[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]].\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = Financier\n\n| salary             = \n| networth           = < \u00a380&nbsp;million\n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Barbara ''n\u00e9e'' Paskin\n| children           = The Hon Jordan Fink,<br> The Hon Alexander Fink,<br> The Hon Gabriella Fink\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| box_width          = \n}}\n:''\"Stan Fink\" redirects here, for American lawyer see [[Stanley Fink]].''\n'''Stanley Fink, Baron Fink''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FCA}} (born 15 September 1957), is a British [[hedge fund]] [[Portfolio manager|manager]], who was formerly CEO of [[Man Group]] plc.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/4537f52e-7ecf-11dd-b1af-000077b07658.html / UK \u2013 Preservation 'a cheap option']. ''Financial Times''. (10 September 2008). Retrieved 19 November 2010.</ref> \n\nIn 2011, Fink became a [[Members of the House of Lords|member of the House of Lords]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn on 15 September 1957 at [[Crumpsall]], Lancashire,<ref name=\"independentacceptable\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/finance-and-philanthropy-the-acceptable-face-of-capitalism-415097.html Finance and philanthropy: The acceptable face of Capitalism \u2013 Business Analysis & Features, Business]. ''The Independent'' (8 September 2006). Retrieved 19 November 2010.</ref><ref name=\"jewishchronicle\">Candice Krieger, [http://www.thejc.com/business/business-features/interview-stanley-fink Interview: Stanley Fink], ''The Jewish Chronicle'', 18 September 2009</ref> his father ran a [[grocery store]].<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/> \n\nFink was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]] before going up to [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/><ref name=\"jewishchronicle\"/>\n\n==Business career==\nFink started his career at the [[Accountant|accountancy firm]], [[Arthur Andersen]],<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/> qualifying as [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] before briefly working for [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars Inc]], then joining [[Citibank]].<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/>\n\nHe served as chief executive officer of [[Man Group]], a hedge fund, from 2000 to 2007.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/conservative/4271998/Stanley-Fink-the-new-Tory-Party-treasurer.html Stanley Fink: the new Tory Party treasurer], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 16 January 2009</ref> Described as the \"godfather\" of the UK [[hedge fund]] [[Financial services|industry]], he is credited with building the Man Group up to its current [[FTSE 100]]-Public company status, the largest listed hedge fund company in the world.<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/><ref>[http://www.cityam.com/index.php?news=14504 London City based Financial, Business and Stock Market News]. ''City AM'' Retrieved on 19 November 2010.</ref> \n\nIn September 2008, he came out of retirement to act as the Chief Executive of International Standard Asset Management (ISAM) in partnership with [[Lord Levy]].<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article4753644.ece ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918005821/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article4753644.ece |date=18 September 2008 }}</ref> Appointed chairman of [[ISAM]] in 2015, he retired from its board in December 2018.\n\nHe serves on the board of [[Marex Spectron]] and was a chairman and largest shareholder of Zenith Hygiene Group for 10 years, which was sold to [[Bain Capital]] in 2018.<ref>[https://www.thecaterer.com/articles/512963/terms-agreed-for-bain-capitals-acquisition-of-zenith-hygiene Terms agreed for Bain Capital\u2019s acquisition of Zenith Hygiene], ''[[The Caterer]]'', 12 October 2017</ref>\n\nLord Fink is a seed investor in Ecometrica, a leading environmental software business which, headquartered in [[Edinburgh]], operates globally. An early investor in New Forests Company, among the largest sustainable forestry businesses in Africa operating in Uganda, Tanzania and Rwanda, the company has become a market leader in the provision of sustainable wood and FSC-certified transmission poles throughout East Africa.<ref>[http://newforests.net/ www.newforests.net]</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 Lord Fink was appointed as Global [[Financial adviser|Special Advisor]] to [[eToro]].<ref>[https://www.institutionalassetmanager.co.uk/2018/07/16/266392/etoro-appoints-special-adviser Global investment platform eToro has appointed Stanley Fink as Special Advisor to the business globally.], ''Institutional Asset Manager'', 16 July 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the Fink family office<ref>[http://www.thefinkfamilyfoundation.org/ www.thefinkfamilyfoundation.org]</ref> was formed, which invests predominantly in PropTech, FinTech and EdTech ventures, and includes: \n\n* British Pearl \u2013 property investment platform: also chairman;<ref>[https://www.britishpearl.com/about British Pearl team], ''British Pearl'', 10 June 2019</ref>\n* Farillio \u2013 speedy, easy law;<ref>[https://www.uktech.news/news/investment-news/legal-tech-startup-farillio-nabs-650000-in-angel-funding-20180927 UK startup Bud raises $20 mn to advance its Open Banking capabilities], ''IBS International'', 4 February 2017</ref>\n* Bud \u2013 leaders in open banking;<ref>[https://ibsintelligence.com/ibs-journal/uk-startup-bud-raises-20-mn-to-advance-its-open-banking-capabilities/ Legal tech startup Farillio nabs \u00a3650,000 in Angel funding], ''UK Tech News'', 27 September 2019</ref>\n* Seneca Learning \u2013 a leading education platform;<ref>[https://www.thetutortrust.org/news/tutor-trust-and-seneca-learning-an-exciting-new-partnership-29th-january-2019 Tutor Trust and Seneca Learning \u2013 an exciting new partnership \u2013 29th January 2019], ''Tutor Trust'', 29 January 2019</ref>\n* PiTops \u2013 a leading STEM, creative learning company;\n* Blackbullion \u2013 helping teach students financial literacy;<ref>[https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-fink/4219/register-of-interests www.parliament.uk], 29 January 2019</ref>\n* Project Etopia \u2013 leading modular building company, also chairman;<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/anyone-else-for-a-game-of-monopoly-jh9ttq0jf ''The Times'']</ref>\n** part owner of hotel group, [[K2]], with 2 leading luxury hotels in Courchevel.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/lord-fink-how-the-godfather-of-the-hedge-fund-made-his-fortune-10042690.html Lord Fink: How the godfather of hedge funds made his fortune], ''[[The Independent]]'', 25 February 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2013 he featured on web reality TV show ''[[Hedge (finance)|HF]] [[Lions Den]]'', when Lord Fink interviewed three emerging hedge fund managers, and allocated $25&nbsp;million in investment between the three [[Investment fund|funds]].<ref>http://www.risk.net/hedge-funds-review/news/2318327/hedge-fund-lions-den-emerging-managers-learn-their-fate</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn January 2009 Fink was appointed Co-Treasurer of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/conservative/4271961/New-Tory-Treasurer-Stanley-Fink-plans-to-blow-Labour-out-of-water.html New Tory Treasurer Stanley Fink plans to blow Labour out of water], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 16 January 2009</ref> \nCreated a [[Life Peer]] on 18 January 2011, he took the title of '''Baron Fink''', ''of [[Northwood, Middlesex|Northwood]] in the [[County of Middlesex]]'';<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59677 |date=21 February 2011 |page=965}}</ref> Lord and Lady Fink were regular guests of [[David Cameron]] at [[Chequers]]<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Chequers guests|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/files/chequersguests.pdf|publisher=Conservative Home}}</ref> and, after the resignation of [[Peter Cruddas]] over a cash-for-access controversy, Lord Fink returned as Treasurer of the Conservative Party, which he had previously given \u00a32.62m:<ref>[http://media.ft.com/cms/c3f0d088-2107-11e1-8a43-00144feabdc0.pdf ''FT Research'': from little acorns...]</ref> he is among the top 20 biggest donors to the Conservative Party.<ref>Elizabeth Rigby, Gavin Jackson, George Parker, 'Tories double number of big City donors in five years: Miliband attacks 'party of Mayfair hedge funds and Monaco tax avoiders',' ''Financial Times'', 5 February 2015, pp. 1; 20</ref>\n\nIn February 2015 Fink was erroneously accused by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader]], [[Ed Miliband]], of undertaking \"[[tax evasion]] activities\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-31428729]</ref> Lord Fink, in reply, stated simply that not only he [[Tax avoidance|avoided tax]], but that \"everyone does tax avoidance at some level\".<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/everyone-avoids-tax-says-lord-fink-after-he-was-named-by-ed-miliband-in-commons-row-10041040.html Evening Standard article on Fink's response]</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn September 2009 Fink was appointed chairman of [[Absolute Return for Kids]].<ref>'Educashun News', ''[[Private Eye]]'', No. 1245 (18 Sep \u2013 1 October 2009), p. 15</ref>\n\nLord Fink is [[School governor|Chairman of Governors]] at [[Ark Burlington Danes Academy]], [[President (corporate title)|President]] of [[Evelina Children's Hospital]] and serves on the [[Board of Trustees]] of the [[Oxford Centre for Hebrew and Jewish Studies]].\n\nIn 2010, he and [[Cherie Blair]] attended a fundraiser for [[Norwood (charity)|Norwood]] of which he is a [[Benefactor (law)|benefactor]].<ref name=\"jewishchroniclelargecrowd\">[http://www.thejc.com/galleries/norwood/a-large-crowd-raises-%C2%A333m-norwoods-services?img=9 A large crowd raises \u00a33.3m for Norwood's services], ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', 23 November 2010</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1981, he married Barbara Paskin;<ref name=\"jewishchroniclelargecrowd\"/> they have two sons, Jordan and Penny, and a daughter, Gabriella.<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/>\n\nLord and Lady Fink live in [[north London]], as well as owning property in France and Spain.<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = \n|image size =\n|notes =\n|year_adopted = \n|coronet = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|40px]] [[Coronet]] of a Baron\n|escutcheon = Azure a Pale between two Skis palewise Argent.\n|crest = A Hedgehog Sable grasping with the dexter forefoot a Menorah of nine branches Or.\n|supporters = On either side a Stag Or supporting a Golf Club head upwards Sable.\n|compartment = \n|motto = '''FABER EST QUISQUE FORTUN\u00c6 SU\u00c6''' ''(Everyone is the maker of his own fortune)''\n|orders = \n|other_elements = \n|banner = \n|badge = \n|symbolism = \n|previous_versions = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fink, Stanley}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Crumpsall]]\n[[Category:People educated at Manchester Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity Hall, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British chief executives]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Lord Fink\n| honorific-suffix ={{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FCA}}\n| image              = Official portrait of Lord Fink crop 2.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| birth_name         = Stanley Fink\n|office7         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start7       = 18 January 2011<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end7       =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth-date and age|15 September 1957}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manchester]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = London\n| nationality        = British\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = [[Financial services]]\n| education          = [[Manchester Grammar School]],<br/>[[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]].\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = Financier\n\n| salary             = \n| networth           = < \u00a380&nbsp;million\n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Barbara ''n\u00e9e'' Paskin\n| children           = The Hon Jordan Fink,<br> The Hon Alexander Fink,<br> The Hon Gabriella Fink\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| box_width          = \n}}\n:''\"Stan Fink\" redirects here, for American lawyer see [[Stanley Fink]].''\n'''Stanley Fink, Baron Fink''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FCA}} (born 15 September 1957), is a British [[hedge fund]] [[Portfolio manager|manager]], who was formerly CEO of [[Man Group]] plc.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/4537f52e-7ecf-11dd-b1af-000077b07658.html / UK \u2013 Preservation 'a cheap option']. ''Financial Times''. (10 September 2008). Retrieved 19 November 2010.</ref> \n\nIn 2011, Fink became a [[Members of the House of Lords|member of the House of Lords]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn on 15 September 1957 at [[Crumpsall]], Lancashire,<ref name=\"independentacceptable\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/finance-and-philanthropy-the-acceptable-face-of-capitalism-415097.html Finance and philanthropy: The acceptable face of Capitalism \u2013 Business Analysis & Features, Business]. ''The Independent'' (8 September 2006). Retrieved 19 November 2010.</ref><ref name=\"jewishchronicle\">Candice Krieger, [http://www.thejc.com/business/business-features/interview-stanley-fink Interview: Stanley Fink], ''The Jewish Chronicle'', 18 September 2009</ref> his father ran a [[grocery store]].<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/> \n\nFink was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]] before going up to [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/><ref name=\"jewishchronicle\"/>\n\n==Business career==\nFink started his career at the [[Accountant|accountancy firm]], [[Arthur Andersen]],<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/> qualifying as [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] before briefly working for [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars Inc]], then joining [[Citibank]].<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/>\n\nHe served as chief executive officer of [[Man Group]], a hedge fund, from 2000 to 2007.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/conservative/4271998/Stanley-Fink-the-new-Tory-Party-treasurer.html Stanley Fink: the new Tory Party treasurer], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 16 January 2009</ref> Described as the \"godfather\" of the UK [[hedge fund]] [[Financial services|industry]], he is credited with building the Man Group up to its current [[FTSE 100]]-Public company status, the largest listed hedge fund company in the world.<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/><ref>[http://www.cityam.com/index.php?news=14504 London City based Financial, Business and Stock Market News]. ''City AM'' Retrieved on 19 November 2010.</ref> \n\nIn September 2008, he came out of retirement to act as the Chief Executive of International Standard Asset Management (ISAM) in partnership with [[Lord Levy]].<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article4753644.ece ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918005821/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article4753644.ece |date=18 September 2008 }}</ref> Appointed chairman of [[ISAM]] in 2015, he retired from its board in December 2018.\n\nHe serves on the board of [[Marex Spectron]] and was a chairman and largest shareholder of Zenith Hygiene Group for 10 years, which was sold to [[Bain Capital]] in 2018.<ref>[https://www.thecaterer.com/articles/512963/terms-agreed-for-bain-capitals-acquisition-of-zenith-hygiene Terms agreed for Bain Capital\u2019s acquisition of Zenith Hygiene], ''[[The Caterer]]'', 12 October 2017</ref>\n\nLord Fink is a seed investor in Ecometrica, a leading environmental software business which, headquartered in [[Edinburgh]], operates globally. An early investor in New Forests Company, among the largest sustainable forestry businesses in Africa operating in Uganda, Tanzania and Rwanda, the company has become a market leader in the provision of sustainable wood and FSC-certified transmission poles throughout East Africa.<ref>[http://newforests.net/ www.newforests.net]</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 Lord Fink was appointed as Global [[Financial adviser|Special Advisor]] to [[eToro]].<ref>[https://www.institutionalassetmanager.co.uk/2018/07/16/266392/etoro-appoints-special-adviser Global investment platform eToro has appointed Stanley Fink as Special Advisor to the business globally.], ''Institutional Asset Manager'', 16 July 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the Fink family office<ref>[http://www.thefinkfamilyfoundation.org/ www.thefinkfamilyfoundation.org]</ref> was formed, which invests predominantly in PropTech, FinTech and EdTech ventures, and includes: \n\n* British Pearl \u2013 property investment platform: also chairman;<ref>[https://www.britishpearl.com/about British Pearl team], ''British Pearl'', 10 June 2019</ref>\n* Farillio \u2013 speedy, easy law;<ref>[https://www.uktech.news/news/investment-news/legal-tech-startup-farillio-nabs-650000-in-angel-funding-20180927 UK startup Bud raises $20 mn to advance its Open Banking capabilities], ''IBS International'', 4 February 2017</ref>\n* Bud \u2013 leaders in open banking;<ref>[https://ibsintelligence.com/ibs-journal/uk-startup-bud-raises-20-mn-to-advance-its-open-banking-capabilities/ Legal tech startup Farillio nabs \u00a3650,000 in Angel funding], ''UK Tech News'', 27 September 2019</ref>\n* Seneca Learning \u2013 a leading education platform;<ref>[https://www.thetutortrust.org/news/tutor-trust-and-seneca-learning-an-exciting-new-partnership-29th-january-2019 Tutor Trust and Seneca Learning \u2013 an exciting new partnership \u2013 29th January 2019], ''Tutor Trust'', 29 January 2019</ref>\n* PiTops \u2013 a leading STEM, creative learning company;\n* Blackbullion \u2013 helping teach students financial literacy;<ref>[https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-fink/4219/register-of-interests www.parliament.uk], 29 January 2019</ref>\n* Project Etopia \u2013 leading modular building company, also chairman;<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/anyone-else-for-a-game-of-monopoly-jh9ttq0jf ''The Times'']</ref>\n** part owner of hotel group, [[K2]], with 2 leading luxury hotels in Courchevel.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/lord-fink-how-the-godfather-of-the-hedge-fund-made-his-fortune-10042690.html Lord Fink: How the godfather of hedge funds made his fortune], ''[[The Independent]]'', 25 February 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2013 he featured on web reality TV show ''[[Hedge (finance)|HF]] [[Lions Den]]'', when Lord Fink interviewed three emerging hedge fund managers, and allocated $25&nbsp;million in investment between the three [[Investment fund|funds]].<ref>http://www.risk.net/hedge-funds-review/news/2318327/hedge-fund-lions-den-emerging-managers-learn-their-fate</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn January 2009 Fink was appointed Co-Treasurer of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/conservative/4271961/New-Tory-Treasurer-Stanley-Fink-plans-to-blow-Labour-out-of-water.html New Tory Treasurer Stanley Fink plans to blow Labour out of water], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 16 January 2009</ref> \nCreated a [[Life Peer]] on 18 January 2011, he took the title of '''Baron Fink''', ''of [[Northwood, Middlesex|Northwood]] in the [[County of Middlesex]]'';<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59677 |date=21 February 2011 |page=965}}</ref> Lord and Lady Fink were regular guests of [[David Cameron]] at [[Chequers]]<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Chequers guests|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/files/chequersguests.pdf|publisher=Conservative Home}}</ref> and, after the resignation of [[Peter Cruddas]] over a cash-for-access controversy, Lord Fink returned as Treasurer of the Conservative Party, which he had previously given \u00a32.62m:<ref>[http://media.ft.com/cms/c3f0d088-2107-11e1-8a43-00144feabdc0.pdf ''FT Research'': from little acorns...]</ref> he is among the top 20 biggest donors to the Conservative Party.<ref>Elizabeth Rigby, Gavin Jackson, George Parker, 'Tories double number of big City donors in five years: Miliband attacks 'party of Mayfair hedge funds and Monaco tax avoiders',' ''Financial Times'', 5 February 2015, pp. 1; 20</ref>\n\nIn February 2015 Fink was erroneously accused by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader]], [[Ed Miliband]], of undertaking \"[[tax evasion]] activities\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-31428729]</ref> Lord Fink, in reply, stated simply that not only he [[Tax avoidance|avoided tax]], but that \"everyone does tax avoidance at some level\".<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/everyone-avoids-tax-says-lord-fink-after-he-was-named-by-ed-miliband-in-commons-row-10041040.html Evening Standard article on Fink's response]</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn September 2009 Fink was appointed chairman of [[Absolute Return for Kids]].<ref>'Educashun News', ''[[Private Eye]]'', No. 1245 (18 Sep \u2013 1 October 2009), p. 15</ref>\n\nLord Fink is [[School governor|Chairman of Governors]] at [[Ark Burlington Danes Academy]], [[President (corporate title)|President]] of [[Evelina Children's Hospital]] and serves on the [[Board of Trustees]] of the [[Oxford Centre for Hebrew and Jewish Studies]].\n\nIn 2010, he and [[Cherie Blair]] attended a fundraiser for [[Norwood (charity)|Norwood]] of which he is a [[Benefactor (law)|benefactor]].<ref name=\"jewishchroniclelargecrowd\">[http://www.thejc.com/galleries/norwood/a-large-crowd-raises-%C2%A333m-norwoods-services?img=9 A large crowd raises \u00a33.3m for Norwood's services], ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', 23 November 2010</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1981, he married Barbara Paskin;<ref name=\"jewishchroniclelargecrowd\"/> they have two sons, Jordan and Penny, and a daughter, Gabriella.<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/>\n\nLord and Lady Fink live in [[north London]], as well as owning property in France and Spain.<ref name=\"independentacceptable\"/>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = \n|image size =\n|notes =\n|year_adopted = \n|coronet = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|40px]] [[Coronet]] of a Baron\n|escutcheon = Azure a Pale between two Skis palewise Argent.\n|crest = A Hedgehog Sable grasping with the dexter forefoot a Menorah of nine branches Or.\n|supporters = On either side a Stag Or supporting a Golf Club head upwards Sable.\n|compartment = \n|motto = '''FABER EST QUISQUE FORTUN\u00c6 SU\u00c6''' ''(Everyone is the maker of his own fortune)''\n|orders = \n|other_elements = \n|banner = \n|badge = \n|symbolism = \n|previous_versions = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fink, Stanley}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Crumpsall]]\n[[Category:People educated at Manchester Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity Hall, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:British chief executives]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Fink,_Baron_Fink"}
{"title_page": "Paul Newey", "text_new": "{{short description|English businessman and poker player}}\n{{Infobox poker player\n|name=Paul Newey\n|nickname=\n|image=Paul Newey 2017.jpg\n|caption=Paul Newey in 2017\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1968|09|06}}\n|hometown=\n|wsop bracelet count=0\n|wsop final tables=1\n|wsop money finishes=4\n|wsop main event best finish rank=726th\n|wsop main event best finish year=2016\n|multi-year wsop winner=\n|wpt titles=0\n|wpt final tables=1\n|wpt money finishes=1\n|ept titles=0\n|ept final tables=6\n|ept money finishes=14\n|updated=2018-02-26\n}}\n\n'''Paul Newey''' (born 6 September 1968) is an [[English people|English]] businessman and semi-professional poker player from [[Dorset]], [[England]] who co-founded [[Ocean Finance]] and later New Wave Ventures.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1991, Newey co-founded [[Ocean Finance]], a loan and mortgage business, in [[Staffordshire]], [[United Kingdom]]. He sold the company in 2006 and left his CEO position in 2009. He later co-founded New Wave Ventures a privately owned investment fund located at Adam House in [[London]].<ref name=\"bloo_Paul\">{{Cite web| title = Paul Newey: Executive Profile & Biography| author = | work = bloomberg.com| date = | accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=11920237&privcapId=130290267}}</ref>\n\nNewey has made the ''[[Birmingham Post]]'' rich list in 2013, 2015 and 2017 ranking 28th, 17th and 20th respectively.<ref name=\"birm_Rich_2013\">{{Cite web| title = Rich List 2013: No.28 - Paul Newey (\u00a3230m)| work = Birmingham Post| date = 2013-01-28| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/rich-list-2013-no28---3908174}}</ref><ref name=\"birm_Rich_2015\">{{Cite web| title = Rich List 2015: No.17 - Paul Newey| last = Strachan | first = Ian| work = Birmingham Post| date = 2015-01-22| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/finance/rich-list-2015-no17---8480994}}</ref> At the end of 2017 his net worth was estimated at [[United States dollar|$]]335 million.<ref name=\"birm_Rich_2017\">{{Cite web| title = Rich List 2017: No.20 - Paul Newey| last = Strachan | first = Ian| work = Birmingham Post| date = 2017-01-26| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/rich-list-2017-no20-paul-12432620}}</ref>\n\n==Gambling==\nNewey is an avid gambler. On 4 January 2005 Newey nearly [[breaking the bank|broke the bank]] at Birmingham's Genting Casino Star City where he won [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3 million and forced owner [[Stanley Leisure]] to issue a profit warning. The casino value declined by 12% as a result of Newey's win.<ref name=\"birm_Rich_2013\"/><ref name=\"thet_High\">{{Cite web| title = High roller hits casino where it hurts with his \u00a33m jackpot| last = Walsh | first = By Dominic| last2 = Nugent | first2 = Helen| work = thetimes.co.uk| date = 2005-01-06| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/high-roller-hits-casino-where-it-hurts-with-his-pound3m-jackpot-wph828csbj0}}</ref> Newey lost his winnings later that month.<ref name=\"tele_High\">{{Cite web| title = High roller loses his \u00a33m spoils| last = Osborne | first = Alistair| work = Telegraph.co.uk| date = 27 January 2005| accessdate = 2018-03-07| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2904421/High-roller-loses-his-3m-spoils.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Newey won four times at the $5,000-a-spin machines in [[Aria Casino]] located in Las Vegas for a total of $1.75 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/watch-moment-lucky-businessman-wins-13736683|title=Moment lucky businessman wins \u00a31MILLION on Las Vegas slot machine|first=Jessica|last=Green|date=9 October 2017|website=birminghammail|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Poker===\nNewey began playing high stakes poker tournaments in 2012 after entering the $1,000,000 [[Big One for One Drop]] event at the [[World Series of Poker]]. Newey was eliminated without cashing on Day 2 by eventual champion [[Antonio Esfandiari]].<ref name=\"poke_Paul\">{{Cite web| title = Paul Newey on Diving Straight into the Poker World, Improving, and More| author = Ryan, Rich| work = PokerNews| date = 2014-01-08| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.pokernews.com/news/2014/01/paul-newey-on-diving-straight-into-poker-17201.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Newey again entered the $1,000,000 One Drop event; this time, he finished 7th, earning $1,418,667.<ref name=\"espn_Dani\">{{Cite web| title = Daniel Colman wins One Drop for $15 million| author = Tuley, Dave| work = ESPN.com| date = 2014-07-02| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = http://www.espn.com/poker/story/_/id/11169110/2014-wsop-daniel-colman-wins-big-one-one-drop}}</ref> Newey has had success in the poker world. As of 2018, Newey has cashed for over $4,800,000.\n\nNewey plays online under the alias \"topdoll827\".<ref name=\"high_Mega\">{{Cite web| title = Mega Rich Businessman Paul Newey revealed as \"topdoll287\" Online| author = Pete| work = HighstakesDB| date = 26 February 2018| accessdate = 2018-02-28| url = https://www.highstakesdb.com/8542-mega-rich-businessman-paul-newey-revealed-as-topdoll287-online.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/player.php?a=r&n=257302 Paul Newey Hendon Mob profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newey, Paul}}\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British investors]]\n[[Category:English poker players]]\n[[Category:British money managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:People from Staffordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English businessman and poker player}}\n{{Infobox poker player\n|name=Paul Newey\n|nickname=\n|image=Paul Newey 2017.jpg\n|caption=Paul Newey in 2017\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1968|09|06}}\n|hometown=\n|wsop bracelet count=0\n|wsop final tables=1\n|wsop money finishes=4\n|wsop main event best finish rank=726th\n|wsop main event best finish year=2016\n|multi-year wsop winner=\n|wpt titles=0\n|wpt final tables=1\n|wpt money finishes=1\n|ept titles=0\n|ept final tables=6\n|ept money finishes=14\n|updated=2018-02-26\n}}\n\n'''Paul Newey''' (born 6 September 1968) is an [[English people|English]] businessman and semi-professional poker player from [[Dorset]], [[England]] who co-founded [[Ocean Finance]] and later New Wave Ventures.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1991, Newey co-founded [[Ocean Finance]], a loan and mortgage business, in [[Staffordshire]], [[United Kingdom]]. He sold the company in 2006 and left his CEO position in 2009. He later co-founded New Wave Ventures a privately owned investment fund located at Adam House in [[London]].<ref name=\"bloo_Paul\">{{Cite web| title = Paul Newey: Executive Profile & Biography| author = | work = bloomberg.com| date = | accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=11920237&privcapId=130290267}}</ref>\n\nNewey has made the ''[[Birmingham Post]]'' rich list in 2013, 2015 and 2017 ranking 28th, 17th and 20th respectively.<ref name=\"birm_Rich_2013\">{{Cite web| title = Rich List 2013: No.28 - Paul Newey (\u00a3230m)| work = Birmingham Post| date = 2013-01-28| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/rich-list-2013-no28---3908174}}</ref><ref name=\"birm_Rich_2015\">{{Cite web| title = Rich List 2015: No.17 - Paul Newey| last = Strachan | first = Ian| work = Birmingham Post| date = 2015-01-22| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/finance/rich-list-2015-no17---8480994}}</ref> At the end of 2017 his net worth was estimated at [[United States dollar|$]]335 million.<ref name=\"birm_Rich_2017\">{{Cite web| title = Rich List 2017: No.20 - Paul Newey| last = Strachan | first = Ian| work = Birmingham Post| date = 2017-01-26| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/rich-list-2017-no20-paul-12432620}}</ref>\n\n==Gambling==\nNewey is an avid gambler. On 4 January 2005 Newey nearly [[breaking the bank|broke the bank]] at Birmingham's Genting Casino Star City where he won [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3 million and forced owner [[Stanley Leisure]] to issue a profit warning. The casino value declined by 12% as a result of Newey's win.<ref name=\"birm_Rich_2013\"/><ref name=\"thet_High\">{{Cite web| title = High roller hits casino where it hurts with his \u00a33m jackpot| last = Walsh | first = By Dominic| last2 = Nugent | first2 = Helen| work = thetimes.co.uk| date = 2005-01-06| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/high-roller-hits-casino-where-it-hurts-with-his-pound3m-jackpot-wph828csbj0}}</ref> Newey lost his winnings later that month.<ref name=\"tele_High\">{{Cite web| title = High roller loses his \u00a33m spoils| last = Osborne | first = Alistair| work = Telegraph.co.uk| date = 27 January 2005| accessdate = 2018-03-07| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2904421/High-roller-loses-his-3m-spoils.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Newey won four times at the $5,000-a-spin machines in [[Aria Casino]] located in Las Vegas for a total of $1.75 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/watch-moment-lucky-businessman-wins-13736683|title=Moment lucky businessman wins \u00a31MILLION on Las Vegas slot machine|first=Jessica|last=Green|date=9 October 2017|website=birminghammail|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Poker===\nNewey began playing high stakes poker tournaments in 2012 after entering the $1,000,000 [[Big One for One Drop]] event at the [[World Series of Poker]]. Newey was eliminated without cashing on Day 2 by eventual champion [[Antonio Esfandiari]].<ref name=\"poke_Paul\">{{Cite web| title = Paul Newey on Diving Straight into the Poker World, Improving, and More| author = Ryan, Rich| work = PokerNews| date = 2014-01-08| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = https://www.pokernews.com/news/2014/01/paul-newey-on-diving-straight-into-poker-17201.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Newey again entered the $1,000,000 One Drop event; this time, he finished 7th, earning $1,418,667.<ref name=\"espn_Dani\">{{Cite web| title = Daniel Colman wins One Drop for $15 million| author = Tuley, Dave| work = ESPN.com| date = 2014-07-02| accessdate = 2018-02-26| url = http://www.espn.com/poker/story/_/id/11169110/2014-wsop-daniel-colman-wins-big-one-one-drop}}</ref> Newey has had success in the poker world. As of 2018, Newey has cashed for over $4,800,000.\n\nNewey plays online under the alias \"topdoll827\".<ref name=\"high_Mega\">{{Cite web| title = Mega Rich Businessman Paul Newey revealed as \"topdoll287\" Online| author = Pete| work = HighstakesDB| date = 26 February 2018| accessdate = 2018-02-28| url = https://www.highstakesdb.com/8542-mega-rich-businessman-paul-newey-revealed-as-topdoll287-online.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/player.php?a=r&n=257302 Paul Newey Hendon Mob profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newey, Paul}}\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:British investors]]\n[[Category:English poker players]]\n[[Category:British money managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:People from Staffordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Newey"}
{"title_page": "Chris Hohn", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sir Chris Hohn\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Christopher Anthony Hohn\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1966|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Addlestone]], [[Surrey]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[University of Southampton]]<br> [[Harvard Business School|Harvard University]]\n| occupation         = [[hedge fund|Hedge fund manager]] and philanthropist\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = Founding and managing [[The Children's Investment Fund Management]]\n| salary             = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Jamie Cooper <small>(divorced)</small>\n| children           = 4\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| networth           = {{increase}} \u00a31.2 billion <small>(Sunday Times Rich List, 2019)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Sir Christopher Anthony Hohn'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ciff.org/about-us/foundation-team/chris-cooper-hohn |title=Chris Cooper-Hohn |publisher=Ciff.org |accessdate=2012-11-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106105247/http://ciff.org/about-us/foundation-team/chris-cooper-hohn |archivedate=2012-11-06 }}</ref> [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]] (born October 1966) is an English billionaire [[hedge fund|hedge fund manager]].\n\nIn 2003, Hohn established [[The Children's Investment Fund Management]] (TCI), a prominent [[value investing|value-based]] investment fund manager noted for long-term, owner orientated engagement with publicly listed companies. Profits generated by the fund were proportionately allocated to [[The Children's Investment Fund Foundation]], a registered charity in England and Wales that focuses on improving the lives of children living in poverty in developing countries.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/8550747/Hedge-fund-boss-Chris-Hohn-gives-away-1bn-in-five-years.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Louise | last=Armitstead | title=Hedge fund boss Chris Hohn gives away \u00a31bn in five years | date=2011-06-01}}</ref> He is known as an [[activist investor]].\n\nAs of 2014, he had given over $4.5B to The Children's Investment Fund Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/hohn-judgment.pdf |title=Court documents|date= 2014|website=www.judiciary.uk |format=PDF|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Hohn is worth \u00a31.2 billion according to the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'' in 2019, an increase of \u00a3200 million from 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sunday-times-rich-list-2019-profiles-101-148-alan-sugar-dx9qlpwcp|title=Rich List 2019: profiles 101-148=, featuring Alan Sugar|last=Times|first=The Sunday|date=2019-05-12|access-date=2019-07-16|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, he had made a \u00a32.4 million donation to purchase around 100 SAMBA II machines to test for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|author=Craig Brierley Communications team |url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/rapid-covid-19-diagnostic-test-developed-by-cambridge-team-to-be-deployed-in-hospitals |title=Rapid COVID-19 diagnostic test developed by Cambridge team to be deployed in hospitals &#124; University of Cambridge |publisher=Cam.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Anthony Hohn was born in October 1966<ref name=\"Companies House\">{{cite web|title=THE CHILDREN'S INVESTMENT FUND FOUNDATION (UK)|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/04370006/officers|website=Companies House|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref> in [[Addlestone]], [[Surrey]].<ref name=FT/> His father Paul<ref>{{cite news|title=City high-flier is UK's most generous donor|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-1599999/City-high-flier-is-UKs-most-generous-donor.html|accessdate=2 March 2015|work=Thisismoney|date=29 June 2006}}</ref> was a Jamaican-born car mechanic of European descent who moved to Britain in 1960, and his mother was a legal secretary from [[East Sussex]].<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2166369/Chris-Hohn-profile-Britains-biggest-charity-donor.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Andy | last=Bloxham | title=Chris Hohn profile: Britain's biggest charity donor | date=2008-06-20}}</ref>\n\nHe was a pupil at St Paul's County Secondary School in Addlestone between 1979 and 1983 gaining 13 [[O Levels]]; he then attended the [[University of Southampton]] from which he graduated in 1988 with first-class honours in accounting and business economics.<ref name=FT>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/da1a54f0-5277-11e1-9f55-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2DEp8INcg TCI goes where other funds fear to tread - FT.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Whilst at Southampton, a tutor advised him to apply for [[Harvard Business School]], where he completed the [[Master of Business Administration]] course.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He graduated in 1993 as a Baker Scholar, meaning he was among the top five percent of all graduates.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Hohn worked for the [[private equity]] group [[Apax Partners]].<ref name=FT /> In 1996 he went to work for [[Perry Capital]], a hedge fund on [[Wall Street]].<ref name=FT /> In 1998 he was made head of Perry's London operations.<ref name=FT /> In his time with Perry, he earned an estimated \u00a375m.\n\nIn 2003, Hohn set up his own hedge fund, [[The Children's Investment Fund Management|The Children's Investment Fund]].  TCI donated regularly to a connected charitable fund, [[The Children's Investment Fund Foundation]], run by his wife.  The original formula involved transfers of 0.5 percent of the fund's assets each year, with a further 0.5 per cent of assets for every year during which the fund achieved returns of more than 11 per cent. It is reported that Hohn established the formulaic charitable link in order to motivate himself.<ref name=FT /> Coinciding with the couple's divorce proceedings, changes set in motion in 2012 led to the splitting up of the fund and the foundation. The fund no longer donates money to the foundation on a contractual basis, though it may do so on a discretionary basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/18/tci-hedge-fund-in-britain-ends-ties-to-charitable-arm/|title=TCI Hedge Fund in Britain Ends Ties to Charitable Arm|date=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nHohn took \u00a3200m in dividend payments in 2018, slightly more than his Children\u2019s Investment (TCI) fund made in profit. This was down from $274m in 2017 and $364m in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/dec/04/hedge-fund-boss-pays-himself-200m-despite-funds-profits-falling|title=Hedge fund boss pays himself \u00a3200m despite fund's profits falling|last=|first=|date=4 December 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> His 2015 earnings of $250 million ranked him 12th among the 25 top earning hedge fund managers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/hedge-fund-managers/list/#tab:overall|title=The Highest-Earning Hedge Fund Managers & Traders|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=2016-11-24}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, it was reported that he had built a \u20ac730m stake in [[Heathrow Airport|Heathrow]] Airport via a range of investment companies jointly taking a 4% stake in Spanish multinational [[Ferrovial]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/10/19/extinction-rebellion-backer-chris-hohn-builds-800m-stake-heathrow/|title=Extinction Rebellion backer Chris Hohn builds \u00a3630m stake in Heathrow|last=Gill|first=Oliver|date=2019-10-19|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2019 it was reported by the Telegraph that Hohn had donated \u00a350,000 to environmental activist group [[Extinction Rebellion]], with a further \u00a3150,000 donated by the Children's Investment Fund Foundation. None of the Charity's money was spent on civil disobedience, it was claimed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/10/extinction-rebellion-funded-charity-set-one-britains-richest/|title=Extinction Rebellion funded by charity set up by one of Britain's richest men|last=Dixon|first=Hayley|date=2019-10-10|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHohn was appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the [[2014 Birthday Honours]] for services to philanthropy and international development.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60895 |date=14 June 2014 |page=b4 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Jamie Cooper, a fellow Harvard graduate student from Chicago, whom he had met at a party during his studies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Timmons |first=Heather |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/26/business/worldbusiness/26hohn.html?_r=0 |title=The Children\u2019s Investment Fund and Its Nonprofit Twin |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=2008-06-26 |accessdate=2012-11-28}}</ref> Upon marriage, they took each other's surnames to become Cooper-Hohn, although he is still widely known as Hohn. The couple went on to have four children, including triplets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/10910675/Hedge-fund-couple-on-track-for-Britains-first-billion-pound-divorce.html |title=Hedge-fund couple Chris Hohn and Jamie Cooper-Hohn on track for Britain\u2019s first billion pound divorce |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2014-06-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 it was reported that Hohn had begun divorce proceedings with his wife.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/10406707/Royal-Mail-hedge-fund-tycoon-Chris-Hohn-posts-his-divorce-papers.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Richard | last=Eden | title=Royal Mail hedge fund tycoon Chris Hohn posts his divorce papers | date=2013-10-27}}</ref> In November 2014, he was set to pay his American-born ex-wife $500 million,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2015/07/28/chris-hohns-activist-hedge-fund-has-big-first-half-of-2015/ |title=Chris Hohn's Activist Hedge Fund Has Big First Half Of 2015 |website=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-28}}</ref> in what is thought to be the biggest divorce settlement ever awarded by an English court.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a2d0ad3a-7652-11e4-a704-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3KM2Id3ex | location=London | work=The Financial Times | first=Jane | last=Croft | title=Chris Hohn in record-breaking $530m divorce settlement | date=2014-11-28}}</ref> In December 2014, he was ordered to pay his ex-wife \u00a3337 million.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/11289857/Sir-Chris-Hohn-ordered-to-hand-over-337m-in-one-of-Englands-biggest-divorce-cases.html |title=Sir Chris Hohn ordered to hand over \u00a3337m in one of England's biggest divorce cases |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2014-12-12 |accessdate=2016-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hohn, Chris}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:English billionaires]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Addlestone]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sir Chris Hohn\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Christopher Anthony Hohn\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1966|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Addlestone]], [[Surrey]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[University of Southampton]]<br> [[Harvard Business School|Harvard University]]\n| occupation         = [[hedge fund|Hedge fund manager]] and philanthropist\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = Founding and managing [[The Children's Investment Fund Management]]\n| salary             = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Jamie Cooper <small>(divorced)</small>\n| children           = 4\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| networth           = {{increase}} \u00a31.2 billion <small>(Sunday Times Rich List, 2019)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Sir Christopher Anthony Hohn'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ciff.org/about-us/foundation-team/chris-cooper-hohn |title=Chris Cooper-Hohn |publisher=Ciff.org |accessdate=2012-11-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106105247/http://ciff.org/about-us/foundation-team/chris-cooper-hohn |archivedate=2012-11-06 }}</ref> [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]] (born October 1966) is an English billionaire [[hedge fund|hedge fund manager]].\n\nIn 2003, Hohn established [[The Children's Investment Fund Management]] (TCI), a prominent [[value investing|value-based]] investment fund manager noted for long-term, owner orientated engagement with publicly listed companies. Profits generated by the fund were proportionately allocated to [[The Children's Investment Fund Foundation]], a registered charity in England and Wales that focuses on improving the lives of children living in poverty in developing countries.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/8550747/Hedge-fund-boss-Chris-Hohn-gives-away-1bn-in-five-years.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Louise | last=Armitstead | title=Hedge fund boss Chris Hohn gives away \u00a31bn in five years | date=2011-06-01}}</ref> He is known as an [[activist investor]].\n\nAs of 2014, he had given over $4.5B to The Children's Investment Fund Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/hohn-judgment.pdf |title=Court documents|date= 2014|website=www.judiciary.uk |format=PDF|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Hohn is worth \u00a31.2 billion according to the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'' in 2019, an increase of \u00a3200 million from 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sunday-times-rich-list-2019-profiles-101-148-alan-sugar-dx9qlpwcp|title=Rich List 2019: profiles 101-148=, featuring Alan Sugar|last=Times|first=The Sunday|date=2019-05-12|access-date=2019-07-16|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, he had made a \u00a32.4 million donation to purchase around 100 SAMBA II machines to test for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|author=Craig Brierley Communications team |url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/rapid-covid-19-diagnostic-test-developed-by-cambridge-team-to-be-deployed-in-hospitals |title=Rapid COVID-19 diagnostic test developed by Cambridge team to be deployed in hospitals &#124; University of Cambridge |publisher=Cam.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Anthony Hohn was born in October 1966<ref name=\"Companies House\">{{cite web|title=THE CHILDREN'S INVESTMENT FUND FOUNDATION (UK)|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/04370006/officers|website=Companies House|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref> in [[Addlestone]], [[Surrey]].<ref name=FT/> His father Paul<ref>{{cite news|title=City high-flier is UK's most generous donor|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-1599999/City-high-flier-is-UKs-most-generous-donor.html|accessdate=2 March 2015|work=Thisismoney|date=29 June 2006}}</ref> was a Jamaican-born car mechanic of European descent who moved to Britain in 1960, and his mother was a legal secretary from [[East Sussex]].<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2166369/Chris-Hohn-profile-Britains-biggest-charity-donor.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Andy | last=Bloxham | title=Chris Hohn profile: Britain's biggest charity donor | date=2008-06-20}}</ref>\n\nHe was a pupil at St Paul's County Secondary School in Addlestone between 1979 and 1983 gaining 13 [[O Levels]]; he then attended the [[University of Southampton]] from which he graduated in 1988 with first-class honours in accounting and business economics.<ref name=FT>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/da1a54f0-5277-11e1-9f55-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2DEp8INcg TCI goes where other funds fear to tread - FT.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Whilst at Southampton, a tutor advised him to apply for [[Harvard Business School]], where he completed the [[Master of Business Administration]] course.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He graduated in 1993 as a Baker Scholar, meaning he was among the top five percent of all graduates.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Hohn worked for the [[private equity]] group [[Apax Partners]].<ref name=FT /> In 1996 he went to work for [[Perry Capital]], a hedge fund on [[Wall Street]].<ref name=FT /> In 1998 he was made head of Perry's London operations.<ref name=FT /> In his time with Perry, he earned an estimated \u00a375m.\n\nIn 2003, Hohn set up his own hedge fund, [[The Children's Investment Fund Management|The Children's Investment Fund]].  TCI donated regularly to a connected charitable fund, [[The Children's Investment Fund Foundation]], run by his wife.  The original formula involved transfers of 0.5 percent of the fund's assets each year, with a further 0.5 per cent of assets for every year during which the fund achieved returns of more than 11 per cent. It is reported that Hohn established the formulaic charitable link in order to motivate himself.<ref name=FT /> Coinciding with the couple's divorce proceedings, changes set in motion in 2012 led to the splitting up of the fund and the foundation. The fund no longer donates money to the foundation on a contractual basis, though it may do so on a discretionary basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/18/tci-hedge-fund-in-britain-ends-ties-to-charitable-arm/|title=TCI Hedge Fund in Britain Ends Ties to Charitable Arm|date=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nHohn took \u00a3200m in dividend payments in 2018, slightly more than his Children\u2019s Investment (TCI) fund made in profit. This was down from $274m in 2017 and $364m in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/dec/04/hedge-fund-boss-pays-himself-200m-despite-funds-profits-falling|title=Hedge fund boss pays himself \u00a3200m despite fund's profits falling|last=|first=|date=4 December 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> His 2015 earnings of $250 million ranked him 12th among the 25 top earning hedge fund managers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/hedge-fund-managers/list/#tab:overall|title=The Highest-Earning Hedge Fund Managers & Traders|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=2016-11-24}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, it was reported that he had built a \u20ac730m stake in [[Heathrow Airport|Heathrow]] Airport via a range of investment companies jointly taking a 4% stake in Spanish multinational [[Ferrovial]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/10/19/extinction-rebellion-backer-chris-hohn-builds-800m-stake-heathrow/|title=Extinction Rebellion backer Chris Hohn builds \u00a3630m stake in Heathrow|last=Gill|first=Oliver|date=2019-10-19|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2019 it was reported by the Telegraph that Hohn had donated \u00a350,000 to environmental activist group [[Extinction Rebellion]], with a further \u00a3150,000 donated by the Children's Investment Fund Foundation. None of the Charity's money was spent on civil disobedience, it was claimed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/10/extinction-rebellion-funded-charity-set-one-britains-richest/|title=Extinction Rebellion funded by charity set up by one of Britain's richest men|last=Dixon|first=Hayley|date=2019-10-10|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHohn was appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the [[2014 Birthday Honours]] for services to philanthropy and international development.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60895 |date=14 June 2014 |page=b4 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Jamie Cooper, a fellow Harvard graduate student from Chicago, whom he had met at a party during his studies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Timmons |first=Heather |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/26/business/worldbusiness/26hohn.html?_r=0 |title=The Children\u2019s Investment Fund and Its Nonprofit Twin |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=2008-06-26 |accessdate=2012-11-28}}</ref> Upon marriage, they took each other's surnames to become Cooper-Hohn, although he is still widely known as Hohn. The couple went on to have four children, including triplets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/10910675/Hedge-fund-couple-on-track-for-Britains-first-billion-pound-divorce.html |title=Hedge-fund couple Chris Hohn and Jamie Cooper-Hohn on track for Britain\u2019s first billion pound divorce |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2014-06-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 it was reported that Hohn had begun divorce proceedings with his wife.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/10406707/Royal-Mail-hedge-fund-tycoon-Chris-Hohn-posts-his-divorce-papers.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Richard | last=Eden | title=Royal Mail hedge fund tycoon Chris Hohn posts his divorce papers | date=2013-10-27}}</ref> In November 2014, he was set to pay his American-born ex-wife $500 million,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2015/07/28/chris-hohns-activist-hedge-fund-has-big-first-half-of-2015/ |title=Chris Hohn's Activist Hedge Fund Has Big First Half Of 2015 |website=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-28}}</ref> in what is thought to be the biggest divorce settlement ever awarded by an English court.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a2d0ad3a-7652-11e4-a704-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3KM2Id3ex | location=London | work=The Financial Times | first=Jane | last=Croft | title=Chris Hohn in record-breaking $530m divorce settlement | date=2014-11-28}}</ref> In December 2014, he was ordered to pay his ex-wife \u00a3337 million.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/11289857/Sir-Chris-Hohn-ordered-to-hand-over-337m-in-one-of-Englands-biggest-divorce-cases.html |title=Sir Chris Hohn ordered to hand over \u00a3337m in one of England's biggest divorce cases |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2014-12-12 |accessdate=2016-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hohn, Chris}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:English hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:English billionaires]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Addlestone]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:English hedge fund managerstoCategory:English financial businesspeopleWikipedia:Categories_for_discussion/Log/2020_February_17#Category:Scottish_stockbrokersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Hohn"}
